{META_DATA}: UNTITLED
{META_DATA}: Cameron Crowe December, 1998
{META_DATA}: UNTITLED
{META_DATA}: 1	FADE IN								1
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A close-shot of a yellow legal tablet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A young hand comes into frame, holding a pencil.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For a few moments, we hear only the soft scratching of pencil on paper, as credits are written in a series of dissolves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The hand carefully erases and corrects an error or two along the way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then the sound of an old friend... the warm crackle of a vinyl record... as we now hear Alvin and the Chipmunks' "Christmas Song."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 2	EXT. PACIFIC OCEAN -- DAY					2
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A lone palm tree rises up into a yellow afternoon sky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind it, the sparkling blue of the Pacific Ocean and the city of San Diego.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A dry, hot Southern California day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Even the wind is lazy, and a little bored.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 3	EXT. NEIGHBORHOOD SHOPPING CENTER - DAY				3
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Santa Claus wears shorts and sandals, ringing a bell as he collects for the Salvation Army.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is Christmas in the Southland.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No snow, no winter wonderland.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just a pleasantly thick heat and an unchanging season, as music continues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Turning the corner, walking into frame is ELAINE MILLER, 35.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is a tall woman, consumed by the fevered conversation she's
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Having with her pale young son WILLIAM, late pre-teens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They stand apart from the other shoppers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All around them is the highly-charged salesmanship of the season... silver glittering fake Christmas trees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hurries her son through the commercial juggernaut, continuing their lively intellectual conversation, when something stops her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Workman is affixing letters to a store-front.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has already placed the MERRY... now he's finishing the XMAS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine is strong, but always pleasant, always clear about her purpose in this life.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Excuse me, I'm a teacher.
{DIALOGUE}: There is no word in The English Language -- "Xmas."
{DIALOGUE}: It's either Merry Christmas... or Happy Holidays.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Workman nods thanks, with faux appreciation, as Mom turns away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Workman shares a look with William, who shrugs - that's my Mom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TITLE: 1969
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 4	EXT. MINI-TRACT CONDO COMPLEX -- DAY				4
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is the new professional-class.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a mini-condo community.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rows of Spanish-styled three-bedroom houses with common walls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Move in on one of these homes, the one without Christmas lights.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the door is a furtive 15 year-old Girl.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She checks her cheek, straightens her hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hides something under her coat, and gathers the proper nonchalance to enter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music fades.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 5	INT. KITCHEN -- DAY						5
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We now hear the dialogue between this lively Mother and her son, as she cooks a pan full of soy-based health-food cutlets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The meal simmers unappetizingly in the pan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Across the kitchen we see William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's a great listener, with a calm and curious face that takes everything in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: - so Livia -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: -- killed everyone off so her son Tiberius could inherit the throne.
{META_DATA}: (thoughtful pause)
{DIALOGUE}: Just like Nixon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William nods, intrigued.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has a good disposition.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The world of knowledge engages him, and he loves what it brings out in his Mom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a small clatter at the front door, as the girl we've just seen enters, barely brushing some chimes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She silently curses herself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Anita, is that you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey Mom!
{DIALOGUE}: I already ate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom moves to the living room to greet William's sister.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William peers into the next room.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 6	INT. LIVING ROOM -- DAY						6
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's almost to her bedroom down the hall when mom catches her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We now discover ANITA, 16, up-close.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is an alluring young Natalie Wood, with a suspicious and sunny smile.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: You sure?
{DIALOGUE}: I'm making soy cutlets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The words "soy cutlets" sends a small shiver through the girl.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: I'm fine.
{DIALOGUE}: Already ate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William stands in the doorway now, watching, monitoring, as Mom moves closer to his sister.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sees something curious about her daughter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Wait.
{DIALOGUE}: You've been kissing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{META_DATA}: (too quickly)
{DIALOGUE}: No I haven't.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (peering at her lips)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes... yes, you have...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: No I haven't.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes you have.
{DIALOGUE}: I can tell.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{META_DATA}: (boldly)
{DIALOGUE}: You can't tell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom steps closer and examines the lips even more carefully.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: To her, everything is a quest for knowledge.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Not only can I tell, I know who it is.
{DIALOGUE}: It's Darryl.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita is stunned silent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She turns slightly to look at herself in a hall mirror, searching for clues, implicating herself immediately.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: And what have you got under your coat?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is the booty Anita didn't want to give up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom picks at the corner of an album cover now visible under her jacket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She withdraws the album.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's Simon and Garfunkel's Bookends.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{META_DATA}: (busted)
{DIALOGUE}: It's unfair that we can't listen to our music!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (weary of the issue)
{DIALOGUE}: Honey, it's all about drugs and promiscuous sex.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: Simon and Garfunkel is poetry!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes it's poetry.
{DIALOGUE}: It's the poetry of drugs and promiscuous sex.
{DIALOGUE}: Look at the picture on the cover...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON BOOKENDS ALBUM COVER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom's fingers at the edges.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We examine the insolent faces on Richard Avedon's classic album cover.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Even Simon and Garfunkle look guilty under her scholarly inspection.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: ... honey, they're on pot.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: First it was butter, then sugar and white flour.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Bacon.
{DIALOGUE}: Eggs, bologna, rock and roll, motorcycles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby, William squirms as he watches the gently escalating conversation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita glances at her brother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He silently urges her to downshift.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She can't.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Then it was celebrating Christmas on a day in September When you knew it wouldn't be "commercialized."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: That was an experiment.
{DIALOGUE}: But I understand -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: What else are you going to ban?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Honey, you want to rebel against knowledge.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm trying to give you the Cliff's Notes on how to live in this world.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{META_DATA}: (simple and direct)
{DIALOGUE}: We're like nobody else I know.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: These are the words that sting Mom most.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a teacher.
{DIALOGUE}: Why can't I teach my own kids?
{META_DATA}: (pats chest)
{DIALOGUE}: Use me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: Darryl says you use knowledge to keep me down.
{DIALOGUE}: He says I'm a "yes" person and you're trying to raise us in a "no" environment!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (immediately, can't help it)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, clearly, "no" is a word Darryl doesn't hear much.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita gasps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ever the peacemaker, William weighs in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby is a poster - "No More War."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Mom --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Everything I say is wrong.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: I can't live here!
{DIALOGUE}: I hate you!
{DIALOGUE}: Even William hates you!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I don't hate her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{META_DATA}: (to William)
{DIALOGUE}: You don't even know the truth!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William looks vaguely confused.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Sweetheart, don't be a drama queen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita takes a breath and then out of her mouth comes the strangled-sounding words of a kid swearing at her parent for the first time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: Feck you!
{DIALOGUE}: All of you!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita runs down the hall to her room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine turns to William, relating to him more as a fellow parent than a child.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, there it is.
{DIALOGUE}: Your sister using the "f" word.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I think she said "feck."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (sputtering)
{DIALOGUE}: What's the difference?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (encouraging)
{DIALOGUE}: Well.
{DIALOGUE}: The letter "u"...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shot moves in on the kid, as we hear the opening strains of The Moody Blues' "Nights in White Satin."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 7	INT. SCHOOL DANCE/GYMNASIUM BATHROOM -- NIGHT			7
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music continues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shot moves along a row of very mature-looking male teenagers, examining themselves in the bathroom mirror.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's the kid with a very mature-looking moustache, the kid proudly sporting full-blown hormonal acne (he slaps on some Hai Karate), the guy to whom puberty has already delivered the face of an adult, complete with long jutting sideburns... and then a blank space at the mirror, as the shot moves down, down, down to find William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is so much younger, without a zit in sight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Puberty is so very distant on his horizon.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 8	INT. DANCE -- NIGHT -- UNDER-CRANKED				 8
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Song continues as we see William's perspective of these much- older looking kids.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Girls now are visible, and they are even more mature than the boys we've just seen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They flirt and glow, arms trailing across the shoulders of the boys.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Whispering in each other's ears, none of them looking down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a troubling experience, to be this close to the alluring world of older teenagers... and to be so invisible to them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VOICE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Are you really in our grade?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 9	INT. JUNIOR HIGH LOCKER ROOM -- DAY				 9
{CHARACTER_NAME}: VOICE
{META_DATA}: (louder)
{DIALOGUE}: Are you really in our grade?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William turns to see tall, adenoidal TIM TOBIN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The most mature looking kid we've seen yet, he challenges William in a loud theatrical tone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a voice right out of Guys and Dolls, which incidentally is the school play in which Tobin had just starred.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William answers in a respectful voice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is desperate for acceptance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBIN
{DIALOGUE}: Hey guys!
{DIALOGUE}: Check it out!
{DIALOGUE}: William doesn't have any pubes!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Others now begin to gather around, examining William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has never been more naked.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GUY # 1
{DIALOGUE}: How old are you man?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBIN
{DIALOGUE}: He's not a man, he's a little baby kid.
{DIALOGUE}: He Doesn't even get zits yet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GUY # 2
{DIALOGUE}: How come you don't have any hair down there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TOBIN
{META_DATA}: (in loud, funny voice)
{DIALOGUE}: Where are your pubes???!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their voices echo off the tiled walls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now everyone is watching the hairless William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is confused by their meanness.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GUY # 2
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: Where are your pubes?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All eyes are on him, waiting for a response.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid's mental wheels turn frantically.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And from somewhere comes an attitude, a swagger, and somehow the perfect line arrives from what could only be a merciful deity.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (cool, dismissive)
{DIALOGUE}: I had 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: I shaved 'em off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a new persona for the kid -- the witty guy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And it works.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Guy #2 cracks up, then others.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William's new accuser is suddenly surrounded by the impressed gales of laughter of these older boys.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Others turn away, on to other things.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tobin stares at William, and then also turns away.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 10 INT. FAMILY CAR -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William jumps into the backseat of the white Ford Country Sedan station wagon, carrying books.
{META_DATA}: ("See ya pubes!")
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom continues driving William and Anita home from school.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (cheerfully, by rote, to William in back)
{DIALOGUE}: Put on your seatbelt.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want you flying through the windshield.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita examines her own un-fastened seatbelt, which Mom hasn't noticed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: We got our annuals today --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (cheerful, automatic)
{DIALOGUE}: "Received" your annual.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (looking at his photo)
{DIALOGUE}: I look so much younger than everyone else.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Enjoy it while you can.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera drifts from Mom to Anita, who can take it no longer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: Mom.
{DIALOGUE}: It's time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (pleasant, pointed)
{DIALOGUE}: Can this wait until we get home?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: Mom, pull over.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell him the truth.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell him how old he is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom pulls over, and stares straight ahead with deep irritation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (as in "be quiet")
{DIALOGUE}: He knows how old he is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: The other kids make fun of him because of How young he looks.
{DIALOGUE}: Nobody includes him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They call him "The Narc" behind his back...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: They do?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: What's a "Narc?"
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{META_DATA}: (bleeding for her brother)
{DIALOGUE}: A Narcotics Officer!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Well what's wrong with that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (ever the peacemaker)
{DIALOGUE}: Come on you guys.
{DIALOGUE}: It's no big deal.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm 12.
{DIALOGUE}: It's okay.
{DIALOGUE}: She skipped me a grade, it's okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Big deal.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a year younger.
{DIALOGUE}: They're 13, I'm 12 --
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Aren't I?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their silence is eloquent.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (confessing, in a rush)
{DIALOGUE}: I also put you in first grade when you were five and never told you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (trembling)
{DIALOGUE}: So... I'm... how old?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A heavy quiet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She and his sister ignore him, as they now debate the subject with each other.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: You lied to him!
{DIALOGUE}: You make such a big deal about the truth and you lied!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (that one hurts)
{DIALOGUE}: He never asked.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: What -- like he's going to ask if he's as old as he thinks he is?
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you realize, this is going to scar him forever?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Honey... sweetheart... don't be Cleopatra.
{DIALOGUE}: We have to be his mother and his Dad.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: You put too much pressure on him!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (apprehensive)
{DIALOGUE}: How... old...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: And when he rebels in some strange and odd way, don't blame me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: ... am I?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (matter of fact)
{DIALOGUE}: I skipped you an extra grade.
{DIALOGUE}: You're eleven.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (horrified, voice crackling)
{DIALOGUE}: ELEVEN?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at his body, the information affects him physically.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: New sounds come from way down deep inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom now begins speed-rapping, trying to stem the leak.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She starts the car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: So you skipped fifth grade.
{DIALOGUE}: There's too much padding In the grades.
{DIALOGUE}: I taught elementary school.
{DIALOGUE}: 5th grade - unnecessary.
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing happens in the 5th grade.
{DIALOGUE}: All Teachers know it, no one talks about it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (still in shock)
{DIALOGUE}: E - leven.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: And you skipped kindergarten because I taught it to you when you were four.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (still horrified, looking at his body)
{DIALOGUE}: This explains... so much...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: You've robbed him of an adolescence!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Adolescence is a marketing tool.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: He's got no "crowd"... no friends...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Okay!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita reaches out to her brother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With the compassion of a saint, she offers this:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: Honey, I know you were expecting puberty.
{DIALOGUE}: You're just going to have to shine it on for a while.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Deeply embarrassed, William shrinks down in the seat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom monitors his face constantly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is raw and sincere... and yes, inspiring:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Who needs a "crowd?"
{DIALOGUE}: You're unique.
{DIALOGUE}: You're two years ahead of everybody.
{DIALOGUE}: Take those extra years and do what you want.
{DIALOGUE}: Go to Europe for a year!
{DIALOGUE}: Take a look around, see what you like!
{DIALOGUE}: Follow your dream!
{DIALOGUE}: You'll still be the youngest lawyer in the country.
{DIALOGUE}: Your own great grandfather practiced law until he was 93.
{DIALOGUE}: Your dad was so proud of you.
{DIALOGUE}: He knew you were a pronominally accelerated child.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: What about me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (heartbroken, can't help herself)
{DIALOGUE}: You're rebellious and ungrateful of my love.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: Well, somebody's gotta be normal around here!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (blinking, still can't believe it)
{DIALOGUE}: Eleven.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 11 INT. WILLIAM'S BEDROOM -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William finishes the last of many candy bars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A mound of wrappers sit just below the mirror.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He examines his face hopefully for zits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nothing coming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We begin to hear Simon and Garfunkel's "America."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 12 INT. LIVING ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita stands in the living room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The song continues playing on the stereo.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: I want to play you a song that explains why I'm leaving, and try to listen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: We can't talk?
{DIALOGUE}: We have to listen to rock music?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 13 EXT. FRONT LAWN -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches sadly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita's good-looking boyfriend DARRYL, a dead ringer for young Stephen Stills, loads her suitcases into a large turqouise Chevy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The suitcases are adorned with plastic stick-on flowers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All coolness is leaving William's life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom watches nearby, worried and helpless.
{META_DATA}: (Their house is more austere, less "fun" than the other front lawns.)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Take good care of her in San Francisco, man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Darryl gives the kid a sub-human look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's invisible, too young to converse with.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: How can she leave such a loving family?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita turns and heads towards them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She focuses on William, placing her hands on his young shoulders.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her face is very close to him now, as she delivers this sage prediction of the future.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: One day you'll be cool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He nods stoically, hopefully.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is utterly lost.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She leans forward and whispers in his ear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Look under your bed.
{DIALOGUE}: It'll set you free.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita shakes hands with Mom, and exits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the car takes off:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: She'll be back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the distance we hear the whoop of her daughter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: YEAHHHHH-HOOOOOOOO.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe not soon...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches wistfully.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He moves away from his mother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She pulls him closer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shot moves in on his slightly fearful face.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 14 INT. DARRYL'S CAR - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita looks back at the receding American Gothic-image of her mother and brother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sister waves to brother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She feels for him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music now shifts to The Who's "Sparks."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 15 INT. BEDROOOM -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William locks the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He reaches under his bed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a black leatherette travel bag, with tartan design.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He unzips the bag -- it's filled with albums.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He flips through the amazing, subversive cache of music.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cream's Wheels of Fire... the seminal Bob Dylan bootleg Great White Wonder... the Rolling Stones' Get Yer Ya Ya's Out... The Beach Boys' Pet Sounds... Abraxas by Santana... Jethro Tull's Stand Up... The Mother's of Invention's We're Only In It For The Money... Led Zeppelin... Crosby, Stills and Nash... Miles Davis' Bitches Brew... and The Who's Tommy... with a note taped to it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: "Listen to Tommy with a candle burning and you will see your entire future..."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The heady effect of all these albums registers, as we see him lighting a candle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TITLE: 1973
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DETAIL SHOT OF NOTEBOOK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A blue school notebook, with ballpoint pen renderings of the names of groups like the Who and Led Zeppelin, complete with carefully drawn thunderbolts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Also, the name LESTER BANGS.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 16 INT. JOURNALISM CLASS -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William, now 15, sits in class with book, Adventures in Journalism.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His hair is shoulder-length.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A dedicated teacher, PATRICIA DEEGAN, walks the aisles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music continues.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 17 EXT. FOOD MACHINES - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William presses the food machine button, pulls an orange from a vending container.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He still looks younger than most of the students... and these days, especially the girls.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 18 EXT. LUNCH COURT -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William sits apart from all the others, under a tree.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He reads intently, happily, as he eats the orange.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a copy of Creem Magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music continues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLOSE ON PHOTOS IN MAGAZINE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera moves across the photos, catching the expressions and fashions of the rock heroes of the day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ian Anderson of Jethro Tull, eyes wide and hair flying as he plays flute.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Neil Young, enigmatic with perfectly patched Levis.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Southern Rock Royalty of The Allman Brothers Band, posing and laughing in front of massive stacks of amps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Marc Bolan of T. Rex, his ringlet-hair backlit by stage lights.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: David Bowie in skin-tight Japanese one- piece attire, onstage with The Spiders From Mars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pete Townsend of the Who, slashing windmill-style at his guitar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Drift down to a by-line - by Lester Bangs.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 19 EXT. PARKING LOT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William walks through the parking lot after school.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everybody now congregates around the new arrival of their lives - their own cars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Arms suddenly clap William on the back, friendly faces smile strangely, laughing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes a few steps and looks up to see... a school official is hurriedly removing something from the high-school marquee.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HIGH-SCHOOL MARQUEE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: which reads: WILLIAM MILLER IS TOO YOUNG TO DRIVE (OR FUCK)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All are laughing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He laughs with them, and turns as his face goes slack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shrugs, marches on.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 20 EXT. DOWNTOWN SAN DIEGO RADIO STATION -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The song we've been listening to is ripped off the turntable by a highly-active man in a red promotional t-shirt proclaiming the greatness of The Guess Who.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is a ferocious, lumbering, music- driven presence, and he fills this small radio studio to the very brim.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is LESTER BANGS, 25, the rarely-seen God of a then new art-form -- Rock Journalism.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Disc-jockey with long- long hair watches helplessly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William views all this through a glass window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stands on the corner of a downtown side street, halfway up a steep incline.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is the only person on the streets this early Saturday morning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reveal that he is watching a live radio show, audible to us through the small p.a. speaker overhead.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DISC-JOCKEY
{DIALOGUE}: Quite an honor to have the World's Greatest Rock Critic... and editor of Creem Magazine, back Home in San Diego for a few days -- Lester Bangs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LESTER BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: What is this hippie station?!
{DIALOGUE}: Where's Iggy Pop?
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you have a copy of Raw Power?!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DISC-JOCKEY
{DIALOGUE}: Lester, isn't it a little early for this?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs searches for the album -- vinyl flying everywhere now, with no regard for album jackets.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Found it!!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 21 EXT. RADIO STATION -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches intently.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs thuds the needle onto a copy of Raw Power.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We're rewarded with a blast of Iggy and the Stooges' "Search and Destroy."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A closer shot on William now watching the whirlwind of anarchy inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lester does an Iggy Pop impression, acting out a story for the d.j. that we cannot hear, never noticing the kid soaking in everything from the other side of this double-glass window.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 22 EXT. RADIO STATION -- DAY -- LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs walks with William on this sharply inclined San Diego street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's early, the streets are silent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs is about fifteen beer pounds overweight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His jeans are loose, his paleness and messy moustache an emblem of the long days and nights spent writing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In there somewhere is a good-looking guy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His hands are thrust deeply into his pockets, and he takes big sweeping steps.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: So you're the one who's been sending me those articles from your school newspaper -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I've been doing some stuff for a local underground paper, too.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: What are you like the star of your school?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: They hate me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: You'll meet them all again on their long journey to the middle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid nods, they walk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, your writing is damn good.
{DIALOGUE}: It's just a shame you missed out on rock and roll.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I did?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Oh yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: It's over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Over?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Over.
{DIALOGUE}: You got here just in time for the death rattle, the last gasp, the last grope.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Well.
{DIALOGUE}: At least I'm here for that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs looks at the much smaller kid, shaking his head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's too late for newcomers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But if the kid's age is an issue, he doesn't mention it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Like a machine-gun:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: What do you type on?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Smith-Corona Galaxis Deluxe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: You like the new Lou Reed?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (automatic)
{DIALOGUE}: The early stuff.
{DIALOGUE}: The new stuff, he's trying to be Bowie, he should be himself.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not a big Lou man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, but if Bowie's doing Lou, and Lou's Doing Bowie, Lou's still doing Lou.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (standing his ground)
{DIALOGUE}: If you like Lou.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Take drugs?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Smart kid.
{DIALOGUE}: I used to do speed and sometimes Nyquil and stay up all night writing and writing, like 25 pages of dribble about, you know, the Guess Who, or Coltrane, just to write, you know, with the music blasting...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Me too.
{DIALOGUE}: The writing part...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For a moment, the serious demeanor dissolves and the oddest thing happens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs laughs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's an odd and charming laugh, the kind a tough guy keeps well-hidden.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It surprised the kid, who smiles back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs stops at the corner, and offers a pleasant but very final nod of the head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Well, alright.
{DIALOGUE}: It's been nice to meet you.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll see you around.
{DIALOGUE}: Keep sending me your stuff.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: See you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: I can't stand here all day talking to my many fans.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WIDE SHOT - SOLITUDE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But neither have anywhere to go on this early downtown morning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They stand for a beat, hands in pockets, on this deserted street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are alone together, there's nobody else in sight.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 23 INT. DINER -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William listens intently as Lester eat a sandwich.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His face is an open book filling with words.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: -- so anyway, you're from San Diego and that's good.
{DIALOGUE}: Because once you go to L.A., you're gonna have friends like crazy but they'll be fake friends, they're gonna try to corrupt you.
{DIALOGUE}: The publicists!
{DIALOGUE}: The bands!
{DIALOGUE}: You got an honest face, they're gonna tell you everything.
{DIALOGUE}: But you CANNOT make friends with the rock stars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid takes out a green collegiate notebook and gestures -- can I make a note?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Cannot make friends with the rock stars.
{META_DATA}: (savage bite)
{DIALOGUE}: That's what's important.
{DIALOGUE}: If you're a rock journalist, a true journalist -- first you will never get paid much.
{DIALOGUE}: But you will get free records from the record company.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid's eyes widen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs, in direct conflict with his brutal writing style, is looking suspiciously like a compassionate softie.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: And they'll buy you drinks, you'll meet girls... they'll try to fly you places for free....
{DIALOGUE}: offer you drugs... I know.
{DIALOGUE}: It sounds great.
{DIALOGUE}: But they are not your friends.
{DIALOGUE}: These are people who want you to write sanctimonious stories about the genius of the rock stars and they will ruin rock and roll and strangle everything we love about it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Privately, William thrills.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Our.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It all sounds great to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He listens to the grouping of the words, every one of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He madly scribbles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: They are trying to buy respectability for a form that is gloriously and righteously -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid leans forward as Lester finds the right word.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: - dumb!
{DIALOGUE}: And you're smart enough to know that.
{DIALOGUE}: And the day it ceases to be dumb is the day it ceases to be real.
{DIALOGUE}: Right?
{DIALOGUE}: And then it will just Become an Industry of Cool.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: ... Industry... of... cool...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: And that's what they want!
{DIALOGUE}: And it's happening right now.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm telling you, you're coming along at a very dangerous time for rock and roll.
{DIALOGUE}: The war is over.
{DIALOGUE}: They won.
{DIALOGUE}: 99% of what passes for rock now... SILENCE is much more compelling.
{DIALOGUE}: It's over.
{DIALOGUE}: I think you should turn around and go back and be... a lawyer or something... but I can see from your face that you won't.
{DIALOGUE}: I can pay you thirty-five bucks.
{DIALOGUE}: Gimme a thousand words on Black Sabbath.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (attempting cool)
{DIALOGUE}: An assignment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LESTER
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: And you should build your reputation on being honest... and unmerciful.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (writing in notebook)
{DIALOGUE}: Honest... unmerciful...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: And if you get into a jam -- call me.
{DIALOGUE}: I stay up late.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bangs reaches across the table, and William watches as he scribbles his number on the back of the kid's green collegiate notebook.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The notebook has just become valuable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They sit together, listening to the beautiful and compelling silence.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 24 INT. FAMILY CAR -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom drives William to the San Diego Sports Arena.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks out the window at the adrenalized concert-goers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She feels protective not just of her son, but an entire generation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William goes over his questions for Black Sabbath.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Look at this.
{DIALOGUE}: An entire generation of Cinderellas and there's no slipper coming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William looks out the window at the sign: TONIGHT - SOLD OUT - BLACK SABBATH with special guest Stillwater.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: You can drop me off here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Black.
{DIALOGUE}: Sabbath.
{DIALOGUE}: Just remember - you wanted to be Atticus Finch in To Kill a Mockingbird.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid doesn't answer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He silently goes over his questions.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: As long as I know this is just a hobby, I'll go along with it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: All I have to do is listen.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what Lester Bangs said.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (dryly)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be waiting right here at eleven 'o clock sharp.
{DIALOGUE}: If you get lost, use the family whistle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He unhooks his seatbelt, stuffs his questions into an orange canvas shoulder-bag and exits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine watches her son disappearing into the stony rock-concert crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a windy night.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everything about this image troubles her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She fights with herself, and then uses the family whistle immediately.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{META_DATA}: (sweetly, too loud)
{DIALOGUE}: Don't take drugs!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fifteen concert-goers turn around instinctively, at the sound of a Mother, and then identify William as the object of her concern.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All around him, we hear:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAPPY CONCERT GOERS
{DIALOGUE}: Don't take drugs!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He winces, nods and moves forward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music echoes from the open windows of many other cars.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 25 EXT. SAN DIEGO SPORTS ARENA BACKSTAGE RAMP -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid tromps down the steep incline leading to a small steel backstage arena door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He rings the buzzer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door wheezes open to reveal the keeper of the San Diego Sports Arena's backstage list.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Famous to all those who attempt to enter, this is SCOTTY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is a wiry, humorless man for whom powerlessness is the theme of his life -- except for those few hours he controls the list.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scotty is only forty but everything about him screams that he's an angry sixty.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm William Miller and I'm here from Creem Magazine to interview the band Black Sabbath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scotty, immediately suspicious, moves to a nearby podium and snaps through three clipboard pages.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He moves back to the door and grabs the handle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCOTTY
{DIALOGUE}: Not on the list.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shuts the door with finality.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid stands silently for a moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks over his shoulder, at two chattering Groupies watching his dilemma from the top of the ramp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They look at him sympathetically, but he turns away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William rings the buzzer again, withdrawing a copy of Creem from his bag.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Sir, I'm a journalist, and here's a copy of the magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The magazine hangs in mid-air.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCOTTY
{DIALOGUE}: You're not on the list.
{DIALOGUE}: Go to the top of the ramp with the girls!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slam.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William stands there for a moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Unsure of what to do next, he looks back to the top of the ramp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rejected by him just moments earlier, the groupies now feign disinterest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bracing himself, William rings again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens slowly this time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scotty stands peering at him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (in a rush)
{DIALOGUE}: What-happens-after-I-go-to-the-top-of- the-ramp with-the-gi -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slam.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lock.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 26 EXT. TOP OF SPORTS ARENA RAMP -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William inches into the realm of the girls at the top of the ramp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The wind whips.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's just him, and two Groupies in their evening best.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They now pretend to barely notice the young journalist who has been banished to stand with them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chattering excitedly, with sophistication far beyond her 17 years, is ESTRELLA.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sports long unruly black hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her partner hangs in the shadows, adjusting shoes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Estrella turns to the kid with great disinterest.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: Who are you with?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (embarrassed to be alive)
{DIALOGUE}: Me?
{DIALOGUE}: I'm with myself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: No, who are you with?
{DIALOGUE}: What band?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I'm here to interview Black Sabbath.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a journalist.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not a..
{DIALOGUE}: you know...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Estrella stares at him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Moving into the parking lot light, introducing herself, is a luminous girl in a green faux-fur trimmed coat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is PENNY LANE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is an inviting warmth and real interest in the way she asks:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: ... you're not a what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (enthralled)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh... I'm just... not a..
{DIALOGUE}: you know.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: Not a "what"?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (charmed)
{DIALOGUE}: You know.
{DIALOGUE}: A "groupie."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two girls are deeply insulted by the word.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: Ohhh!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Sorry, I -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: We.
{DIALOGUE}: Are not.
{DIALOGUE}: "Groupies."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Estrella indicates Penny with great reverence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: This is Penny Lane, man.
{DIALOGUE}: Show some respect.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: -- sorry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny steps closer, focusing completely on the kid.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind her, concert-goers throw a few woo-woos their way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She seems not to hear them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: "Groupies" sleep with rock stars because they want to be near someone famous.
{DIALOGUE}: We are here because of the music.
{DIALOGUE}: We are Band Aids.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: She used to run a school for Band Aids.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: We don't have intercourse with these guys.
{DIALOGUE}: We support the music.
{DIALOGUE}: We inspire the music.
{DIALOGUE}: We are here because of the music.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William is nodding like a doll in a dashboard window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Listening.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: Marc Bolan broke her heart, man.
{DIALOGUE}: It's famous.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: It's a long story.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm retired now.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just visiting friends.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: She was the one who changed everything.
{DIALOGUE}: She said "no more sex, no more exploiting our bodies and hearts... "
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: "... just blow-jobs, and that's it."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, see, now I get the difference.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shot drifts off him and picks up, out of the darkness, another breathless girl teetering on tall shoes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is in the vicinity of 16.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her black hair is cropped short and died red, just like the cover of Bowie's Aladdin Sane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is POLEXIA, the voluptuous one, from Riverside.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{META_DATA}: (the usual greeting)
{DIALOGUE}: It's all happening.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all happening.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: Polexia!!
{DIALOGUE}: Did you tell Sabbath we were going to be here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{DIALOGUE}: I talked to Dick with Stillwater, I talked with Sabbath.
{DIALOGUE}: They're all dying to see us.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all happening.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: This is our journalist friend.
{DIALOGUE}: Journalist Friend, meet Estrella Starr, and Polexia Aphrodisia.
{DIALOGUE}: And you are --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silent beat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His name lands like a thud.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{DIALOGUE}: Here comes Sabbath!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: Ozzy!!!
{DIALOGUE}: Tony!!!
{DIALOGUE}: It's us!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long black limo with darkened windows swishes past, beeps twice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The metal backstage gate rises and the limo rolls inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then silence again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The girls do not discuss being rebuffed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: I think I saw Sapphire in there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{META_DATA}: (can't hold it in any longer)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: I was with Ian Hunter all night at Rodney's Last night.
{DIALOGUE}: Wanna see his spoo?
{DIALOGUE}: I saved it in a baggie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She opens her purse and shows the girls something inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William edges away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{META_DATA}: (peering into purse)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm really happy he's doing so well.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{META_DATA}: (regarding what's in purse)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: I know he's such a talented guy.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, look at him.
{DIALOGUE}: Who deserves it more?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{META_DATA}: (looking in purse)
{DIALOGUE}: Nobody -- he's so sweet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{META_DATA}: (with compassion)
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you just root for him, you know.
{DIALOGUE}: To go that little distance between good and great?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Wait.
{DIALOGUE}: That's not his.
{DIALOGUE}: I would know his.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A very odd look on his face, William now cranes for a discreet look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: What's in that purse?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BAM -- THE BACKSTAGE DOOR OPENS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Out steps SAPPHIRE, 19, a tall girl with taller platforms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Heavy eye-makeup.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her accent is Texan, with odd traces of English.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In one hand is a half-drained bottle of champagne.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the other, a fistful of backstage passes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: Does anybody remember laugh-tah?
{META_DATA}: (as they turn)
{DIALOGUE}: Come and GET 'EM!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The girls scream and happily head down the ramp to Sapphire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny looks back and grabs William with a well-placed arm hooked around his.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He joins the clacking sea of legs moving down the ramp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sapphire slaps passes on the girls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Scotty (The Keeper of the Backstage List) watches, Penny now slips William forward for a pass.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCOTTY
{DIALOGUE}: Oh no.
{DIALOGUE}: Not this one --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{META_DATA}: (off William)
{DIALOGUE}: Who brought Opie?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid looks over his shoulder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Who's Opie?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: He's with us.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCOTTY
{META_DATA}: (hand blocking William)
{DIALOGUE}: He wasn't with you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{META_DATA}: (to Scotty)
{DIALOGUE}: Are you going to turn this into a Thing?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCOTTY
{DIALOGUE}: All of you can wait outside!
{DIALOGUE}: Top of the ramp!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to cause a Thing.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll wait.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{META_DATA}: (privately, to William)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll go take care of this.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sadly, they leave him behind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The thundering arena sound of the collecting crowd, the p.a. system blasting Yes' "Roundabout"... purposeful roadies carrying guitar cases... the glimpse of backstage rock and roll... everything he wants to be a part of is on the other side of this door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then it shuts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stands alone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the top of the ramp, a tour bus unloads.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It reads -- STILLWATER TOUR 73.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Moving loudly out of the bus is the opening band.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is Stillwater.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Four road-weary band members, and their road manager.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Voices booming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: RUSSELL HAMMOND, 27, presses the buzzer with the nose of his guitar-case.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's obvious from moment one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is the star of the band, the charismatic one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's tired.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're late.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William recognizes him instantly, as the guitarist stretches.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The buzzer goes unanswered.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid is invisible to him, as the others now arrive behind Russell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tour/band manager DICK ROSWELL, 27, follows, loudly banging on the steel door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has the flaxen-haired look of a former hippie, but he carries the emblem of a real pro -- the newest silver Halliburton briefcase covered with backstage passes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His direction is always - forward.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Let us in, we're Stillwater!
{DIALOGUE}: We're on the show!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William is surrounded by them now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They stand together under the single lightbulb, familiar faces, a live-action album cover.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: JEFF BEBE the singer, his shiny black hair hanging in sheets around his head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ED VALLENCOURT the quiet drummer, his long arms hanging limply at his sides.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His is a face made for the background.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LARRY TURNER the compact bass-player.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick now kicks at the door with his foot, as William produces a copy of Creem Magazine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (to Dick)
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, I'm a journalist.
{DIALOGUE}: I write for Creem Magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Once again, the magazine hangs there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He can't give it away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: The enemy!
{DIALOGUE}: A rock writer!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (struggling forward)
{DIALOGUE}: I'd like to interview you or someone from the band.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{META_DATA}: (busy, running behind)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry but could you please fuck off?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William blinks a little, takes it in stride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell sizes him up, moving in the background.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: I could do that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: You guys never listened to our records.
{DIALOGUE}: You're all just frustrated musicians.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know what your magazine SAID about us?
{DIALOGUE}: What was it - "the singer's incessant cater walling distracts From an assault with no clear purpose."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LARRY
{META_DATA}: (in background)
{DIALOGUE}: That was Rolling Stone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Fuck off anyway.
{DIALOGUE}: We play for fans, not critics.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stung, William shrugs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's been a terrible night, but at least thrillingly so.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Russell.
{DIALOGUE}: Jeff.
{DIALOGUE}: Ed.
{DIALOGUE}: Larry.
{META_DATA}: (can't help it)
{DIALOGUE}: I really love your band.
{DIALOGUE}: I think the song "Fever Dog" is a big step forward for you guys.
{DIALOGUE}: I think you guys producing it yourselves, instead of Glyn Johns, was the right thing to do.
{DIALOGUE}: And the guitar sound was incendiary.
{META_DATA}: (gestures with fist)
{DIALOGUE}: Way to go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns and leaves, beginning his long trek back up the ramp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell looks at the others.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That kind of love is hard to give up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (good humored, yelling)
{DIALOGUE}: Well don't stop there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, come back here!!
{DIALOGUE}: Keep going!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They wave him back, as the backstage door opens again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid moves back down the ramp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They herd him in with them, through the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scotty quickly spots the kid and squares off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell notes the kid's swirling emotional state, shoves him forward.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCOTTY
{DIALOGUE}: Not this one.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: He's with us.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCOTTY
{DIALOGUE}: He's not with you.
{DIALOGUE}: He's not with them.
{DIALOGUE}: He's not on the list.
{DIALOGUE}: He's not coming in.
{DIALOGUE}: And this is my arena.
{DIALOGUE}: And furthermore -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russel craves the confrontation and moves forward closer to Scotty.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SCOTTY (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: - have a good time tonight.
{DIALOGUE}: Welcome to San Diego.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 27 INT. BACKSTAGE HALLWAY -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The band moves quickly down the hallway, with William moving to keep up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A young and grizzled red-haired roadie, RED DOG, catches them on the way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The band swarms around him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Red Dog!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RED DOG
{DIALOGUE}: We're playing here tomorrow night.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{META_DATA}: (aside, to the kid)
{DIALOGUE}: This is Red Dog, the Allman Brothers Band's number one roadie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russel clamps an arm around Red Dog's neck.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: How're the guys?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RED DOG
{DIALOGUE}: Havin a ball, man.
{DIALOGUE}: When we have a party, we have an Allman Brothers Band party.
{DIALOGUE}: Everybody boogies.
{DIALOGUE}: Everybody gets off.
{DIALOGUE}: It's family, man.
{DIALOGUE}: We all got These now.
{META_DATA}: (flashes new mushroom tattoo on forearm)
{DIALOGUE}: We'll see you guys in Boston, right?
{META_DATA}: (specifically to Russell)
{DIALOGUE}: Dicky and Gregg send you their love.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera catches flash of envy on the face of Jeff Bebe, as Stillwater sweeps forward into a small dressing room.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 28 INT. DRESSING ROOM -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dressing room activity swirls around him, as William simply listens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He holds a small microphone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His stoic look gives away little of the full body rush he's experiencing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the other band members drift across frame, Russell Hammond, a true rock and roll believer, speaks as he straps on his guitar and gets ready for the show.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: To the kid, every word is reckless gem.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: ... and it's okay, because rock and roll is a LIFESTYLE... and a way of thinking and it's not about money and "popularity!"
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Some money would be nice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff sprays some shaving cream into his palm, and rubs it into his scalp - poor man's mousse.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: - but it's a voice that says here I am... and FUCK YOU if you can't understand me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell smooths the strings of his guitar with a small cloth from his guitar case.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid notices all these close-up details of rock.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: And one of those people is gonna save the world and that means that ROCK AND ROLL CAN SAVE THE WORLD -- all of us together.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid's eyes dance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He checks to make sure he's getting the recording.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He listens intently.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: And the chicks are great.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: But we didn't do it for that!
{DIALOGUE}: We are here because we needed to fuckin be here, not just 'cause we needed to away from Troy, Michigan, WHICH WE DID... but what it all comes down to is that thing.
{DIALOGUE}: The Indefinable Thing, when people catch something from your music, the thing you put into it.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm talking about... what am I talking about?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (elegantly)
{DIALOGUE}: The buzz?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: THE BUZZ!
{DIALOGUE}: And the chicks, the whatever, is an off-shoot of THE BUZZ.
{DIALOGUE}: And like -- you saying you liked "Fever Dog?"
{DIALOGUE}: That is the fucking buzz, man.
{DIALOGUE}: All we get are these fucking old-ass interviewers who don't understand, don't LISTEN, don't appreciate why we are here, which is the fuckin' BUZZ.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William nods, holds his microphone steady.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell tunes his guitar, ripping through unamplified guitar licks as he speaks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff hustles to reclaim his own connection to the interviewer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: The next album will be even better.
{DIALOGUE}: More texture.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: But... it's not what you put in, is it?
{DIALOGUE}: It's what you leave out.
{DIALOGUE}: Listen to... listen to Marvin Gaye...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell's face grows rapturous as he discusses this piece of music.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: A song like "What's Going On."
{DIALOGUE}: That single "woo" at the end of the second verse - you know that woo - that single "woo."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (proudly)
{DIALOGUE}: I know that, "woo."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (he does it)
{DIALOGUE}: That's what you remember.
{DIALOGUE}: The silly things, the little things... there's only one, and it makes the song.
{DIALOGUE}: It's what you leave out.
{DIALOGUE}: That's rock and roll.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William nods, says nothing, keeps the microphone pointed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Activity surrounds him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{META_DATA}: (impressed)
{DIALOGUE}: We used to talk more about this stuff.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: See, this is maybe the most honest we've ever been in an interview because you know our music.
{DIALOGUE}: You're the first press guy we've made friends with.
{DIALOGUE}: We don't normally talk like this to them.
{DIALOGUE}: And you're supposed to be The Enemy!
{DIALOGUE}: What are you - 18?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: There you go.
{DIALOGUE}: Still young enough to be honest.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{META_DATA}: (walkie talkie crackling)
{DIALOGUE}: Ten minutes 'till showtime, anyone who isn't in the band -- out!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell takes a last swig of beer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A roadie whisks his guitar away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: All this luggage is going to L.A.!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William is swept out in the chaos of the pre-show ritual, past the pile of luggage by the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a colorful heap of suitcases, featuring colorful laminated band tags, each with a number.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 29 INT. BACKSTAGE STEPS -- NIGHT -- MINUTES LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William sits on the backstage steps, writing feverishly in his notebook.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind him, two steps higher, Penny Lane scoots into place.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: I found you a pass.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (amped, distracted)
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks.
{DIALOGUE}: I got in with Stillwater.
{META_DATA}: (as he writes)
{DIALOGUE}: The guitarist, Russel Hammond, he just thoroughly opened up.
{DIALOGUE}: He is by far the best and most honest interview I've ever done.
{META_DATA}: (she nods)
{DIALOGUE}: I've only done two, but you know.
{DIALOGUE}: He's number one.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: You're learning.
{DIALOGUE}: They're much more fun on the way up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William nods, still scribbling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She eases down into place on the step next to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her proximity cause him to look at her, his eyebrows rising.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She smooths them down with two single fingers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: How old are you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Eighteen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: Me too.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: How old are we really?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Seventeen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: Me too.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Actually I'm 16.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: Me too.
{DIALOGUE}: Isn't it funny?
{DIALOGUE}: The truth just sounds Different.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (confesses)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm 15.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: You want to know how old I really am?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (immediately)
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks upstairs, soaking in the sound of another band tuning up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music is her religion.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: How did you get started in all this?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: It's a long story.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (quick study)
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: We live in the same city.
{DIALOGUE}: We should be friends.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She takes his backstage pass form his shirt and puts it on his thigh - the cooler location.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby, the dressing room door opens, and the Stillwater exits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Excitement level rises as they mass in the hallway with instruments.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear the amped voice of Russell growing nearer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: The Enemy!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He approaches, as William stands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny watches, hanging out of Russell's eyesight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Standing in the supercharged hallway, the kid is anxious to introduce his new friends.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Russell, this is Penny Lane.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{META_DATA}: (stepping into view)
{DIALOGUE}: Pleasure.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Penny Lane?
{DIALOGUE}: Like the song, right?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: Have we met?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THEY SHAKE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And do not let go, for too long.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is history in their shake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their eyes tell all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shot takes us to William, who puts two and two together.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It isn't hard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They clearly know each other.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Well.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I guess you've... you've met.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Penny Lane!
{DIALOGUE}: God's gift to rock and roll!!
{DIALOGUE}: You're back!
{META_DATA}: (privately)
{DIALOGUE}: Marc Bolan.
{DIALOGUE}: Please.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Other band members pass, adjusting clothes for show time, waiting in the hallway... and now singing the Beatles song "Penny Lane."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, let's go.
{META_DATA}: (noting kid's shyness)
{DIALOGUE}: Both of you.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 30 INT. BACKSTAGE -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: House lights go down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cheers rise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick's flashlight dances on the ground just in front of them, guiding their way in the dark to the stage steps.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: - get in the huddle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell pulls William into the band's huddle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SHOT LOOKING UP AT THEM
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their band ritual, psyching together, arms on each other's shoulders in a circle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They sing a dew lines of the classic "Train Kept A-Rollin'" (or "Go See Cal" from the Cal Worthington ad) They all touch feet, and then break, heading for the stage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell directs Penny to his side of the stage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid follows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Plugging in, still in darkness, Russell hits a practice chord -- thwack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He steps on effects pedal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Applause.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: (Adlib onstage private patter, between members, goading each other -- the stuff no audience ever hears) Twenty feet away, Dick prepares to address the crowd from the darkened stage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is his favorite moment of the evening, the highlight of his job.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: From Troy, Michigan.
{DIALOGUE}: Please welcome --
{META_DATA}: (importantly)
{DIALOGUE}: Stillwater.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Light hits the stage, and the band launches into their opening song, "If You Say Nothing."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Audience response is strong.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shot lingers on the face of William as he soaks in the most undeniably exciting moment of any concert, the first thirty seconds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff the singer grabs the microphone and launches into some vocal pyrotechnics.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell looks over to Penny and William, at stage right, grinning, pretending to trip on his cord, an elegant show-off move of a musician who is now where he belongs... before seriously stepping forward for the first guitar lead of the night.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid looks over to see Penny watching Russell.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 31 EXT. BACKSTAGE -- NIGHT -- LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cases are shut and rolled toward the trucks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stillwater heads for their bus.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff the singer says goodbye to Estrella Starr, like a sailor leaving port.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell lingers behind, saying goodbye to William, loading his own equipment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Black Sabbath passes with entourage, heading to the stage.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (privately)
{DIALOGUE}: So.
{DIALOGUE}: You want to come up to L.A., we'll be at the "Riot House" all week.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: "The Riot House?"
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: The Continental Hyatt House!
{DIALOGUE}: It's on Sunset Strip.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (attempting cool)
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All the while, just over the kid's shoulder, Russell scans the backstage crowd of hangers-on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking perhaps for Penny Lane.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Let's blow this burg!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (exiting)
{DIALOGUE}: Well tell your friend Miss Penny Lane to Call Me.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell her "It ain't California without her.
{DIALOGUE}: We want her around like last summer."
{DIALOGUE}: Say it like that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Got it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (returns, whispers)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I'm under the name - Harry Houdini.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{META_DATA}: (exiting, to William)
{DIALOGUE}: The Enemy!!
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah!!
{DIALOGUE}: Come to L.A., we'll take some more.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell joins Jeff, exiting and laughing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A good show is still in the air.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Later Jeff!
{DIALOGUE}: See you, Dick.
{DIALOGUE}: Larry.
{DIALOGUE}: Ed.
{META_DATA}: (and now the roadies)
{DIALOGUE}: Mick, Gregg, Red Dog, Scully, Frosty, Estrella, The Wheel!
{DIALOGUE}: ROADIES			 DICK Laterrrr!
{DIALOGUE}: We'll see you down the line.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William is deliriously happy, hands upraised.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns to see Penny.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: PENNY!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{META_DATA}: (calming him)
{DIALOGUE}: Hey.
{DIALOGUE}: Hey.
{DIALOGUE}: Be cool.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: You just missed Russell!
{DIALOGUE}: He says he's at the "Riot House" all week and to call him.
{DIALOGUE}: He's under the name Harry Houdini.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know about the "Riot House?"
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: I think I've heard of it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: He had a message for you!
{DIALOGUE}: He said, "It's not California without you.
{DIALOGUE}: We want you around like last summer."
{META_DATA}: (consults notebook)
{DIALOGUE}: Actually he said "ain't."
{DIALOGUE}: "It ain't California - "
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: I get the gist.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: How well do you guys know each other?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She smiles privately.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: I got it.
{DIALOGUE}: No problem.
{DIALOGUE}: Long story.
{DIALOGUE}: Alright!
{DIALOGUE}: I gotta go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elsewhere in the arena, Black Sabbath is performing "Sweet Leaf."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid could care less.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has bonded with Stillwater.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He heads for the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny walks with him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's loving it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They pass a still-scowling Scotty, flashing passes, as they exit out into the ramp area.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 32 EXT. SPORTS ARENA -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny takes out an eyeliner pencil, writes her number on the back of his green notebook.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY LANE
{DIALOGUE}: Call me if you need a rescue.
{DIALOGUE}: We live in the same city.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I think I live in a different world.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They stand in the night air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The parking lot is largely silent now, save for the thudding bass sounds of Black Sabbath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the distance, we hear Elaine's insistent whistle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Speaking of the world.
{DIALOGUE}: I've made a decision.
{META_DATA}: (a very serious secret)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to live in Morocco for one year.
{DIALOGUE}: I need a new crowd.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is a rapt audience for this flashy girl.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Do you want to come?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the distance, we hear the family whistle growing louder.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: It's a plan.
{DIALOGUE}: You've got to call me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: It's all happening.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: It's all happening.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He nods cooly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He waits until she turns, and the sprints through the parking lot, to the distant family whistle.
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT:
{META_DATA}: FADE IN:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 33 ON TAPE RECORDER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William's fingers work the clunky keys, pressing rewind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear a snippet of the intense and lively Stillwater interview, full of overlapping and barely discernible voices.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Meticulously, he untangles the voices, especially Russell's, as he transcribes.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILLIAM'S BEDROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The work of a journalist, as William sits at his Smith-Corona Galaxis.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a knock at the window, and William scoots back in his chair to see a familiar face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is Darryl, his sister's old boyfriend.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William opens the window.
