{DIALOGUE}: And pack light this time.
{DIALOGUE}: Jesus.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They kiss.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The motorcycle speeds by again, just outside.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 42 INT. HALLWAY -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The hallways are crowded, as William looks at the closed door of the ice room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans against the wall, alone now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trying to look like he belongs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind him, most of the band has disappeared into other rooms, leaving only hangers-on in their places.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 43 INT. ROLLING STONE MAGAZINE -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We pan across cubicles bustling with laid-back fervor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: These are the San Francisco-based main offices of Rolling Stone Magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We have arrived for the waning days that this magazine could still be called, with a straight-face, an "underground" publication.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their mounting success crowds the edges of every frame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera catches the Annie Leibowitz portraits that hang on the walls -- Lennon, Jagger, Rod Stewart, James Taylor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We find editor BEN FONG-TORRES, 29, in his cramped cubicle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sitting nearby is curly-haired and mustachioed Star Staff writer, DAVID FELTON, 32, who smokes his cigarettes with a long holder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Felton reads one of William's articles, chuckling.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN FONG-TORRES
{DIALOGUE}: William Miller?
{META_DATA}: INTERCUT:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILLIAM'S BEDROOM -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William is on the phone in his own small room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: This is he.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: Crazy.
{DIALOGUE}: William, this is Ben Fong- Torres.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm the music editor at Rolling Stone Magazine.
{DIALOGUE}: We've got a copy of your stories from the San Diego Door.
{DIALOGUE}: This is the same William Miller?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William instantly, nervously alters his voice to sound older.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Yes it is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{META_DATA}: (rifling through tearsheets)
{DIALOGUE}: Voice of God, howling dogs, the spirit of rock And roll... this is good solid stuff.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (immediately, suddenly deeper)
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks... thanks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: You should be writing for us.
{DIALOGUE}: Any ideas?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (voice now to deep)
{DIALOGUE}: How about Stillwater?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: Crazy.
{DIALOGUE}: New album... their third... starting to do something.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ben shuffles through papers, looking for a tour itinerary on his promotional-material laden-desk, automatically plotting the piece aloud.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN (cont'd)
{META_DATA}: (pleasant, terse)
{DIALOGUE}: Stillwater.
{DIALOGUE}: Hard-working band makes good.
{DIALOGUE}: Get 'em to respond to the critics who dismissed the first two albums as workmanlike.
{DIALOGUE}: Guitarist is the clear star of the band.
{DIALOGUE}: Crazy.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's do three- thousand words.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll catch up to them on the road.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll set up billing -- don't let the band pay for anything.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (affecting casualness)
{DIALOGUE}: Sounds good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: We can only pay -- lemme see, three- thousand words -- seven hundred dollars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid's eyes widen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Alright, a grand.
{DIALOGUE}: What's your background?
{DIALOGUE}: You a journalism major?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (deeply)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: What college --
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ELAINE'S HOUSE -- CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine now gets on the extension.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Honey, I need you to do that thing that fixes the garbage disposal --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hangs up.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILLIAM'S BEDROOM -- CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid is paralyzed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I know how my lady gets when I don't Snap to it -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Crazy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: Crazy!
{DIALOGUE}: I'll let you go.
{DIALOGUE}: Call me at the San Francisco office tomorrow.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 44 INT. LESTER BANGS HOME -- LATE NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The great Lester Bangs stands in the promotional album-clogged bedroom of his Birmingham, Michigan, home/office at Creem Magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is nothing in frame that does not deal with music.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the background, a scratchy and chaotic Coltrane record.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LESTER BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Beware Rolling Stone Magazine.
{DIALOGUE}: They will change your story, they'll re- write it and turn it into swill.
{DIALOGUE}: Beware!!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: But besides that, what would be wrong with it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LESTER BANGS
{META_DATA}: (laughs, entertained)
{DIALOGUE}: You have starry eyes, my friend.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Look.
{DIALOGUE}: Do the story.
{DIALOGUE}: It's a good break for ya.
{DIALOGUE}: But remember this --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid listens intently, and makes notes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LESTER BANGS (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: ... don't do it to make friends with people who are trying to use you to further the big business desire to glorify worthless rock stars like Stillwater.
{DIALOGUE}: And don't let those swill merchants re-write you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (still copying)
{DIALOGUE}: ... swill merchants...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LESTER BANGS
{DIALOGUE}: Now.
{DIALOGUE}: What are you listening to?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 45 EXT. TEACHER'S LOUNGE -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William knocks on the teacher's lounge door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Teacher answers, protective of their sanctuary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (urgently)
{DIALOGUE}: I need to talk to Mrs. Deegan, from Journalism.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Deegan appears in the doorway.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 46 EXT. WILLIAM'S HOME -- LATE AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sun is still shining.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's late afternoon, as Elaine Miller exits her car and arrives home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sees a few extra cars in the driveway, is immediately suspicious.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 47 INT. LIVING ROOM -- LATE AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine arrives to find William, Mrs. Deegan and Darryl awaiting her in the living room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a 1973-style intervention.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They wear sunny, compassionate smiles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever it is, the answer is no.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN
{DIALOGUE}: Elaine, we need to talk to you.
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing is wrong.
{DIALOGUE}: I am a teacher.
{DIALOGUE}: You're a teacher.
{DIALOGUE}: We speak the same language.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom sits down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is fully engaged and worried, her natural state.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Now I'm not a jump-up-and-down person, but something wondrous has happened to William.
{DIALOGUE}: And you have every reason to be happy...
{META_DATA}: (knows her)
{DIALOGUE}: ... and calm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carefully gauging Elaine's face, the teacher continues.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: William has been gifted with a shining opportunity in the world of journalism.
{DIALOGUE}: Through a love of music, and at an oddly-young age, he has received a major assignment from a national publication called Rolling Stone Magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Deegan produces a copy, and places it on Elaine's lap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It sits there like the plague.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Now you are rather famously not a fan of rock music, but such are the ironies of life, that happens to be the very topic of William's assignment -
{META_DATA}: (cheerfully)
{DIALOGUE}: - rock music.
{DIALOGUE}: A band.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (warily, to Darryl)
{DIALOGUE}: Honey, what are you doing here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DARRYL
{DIALOGUE}: Moral support.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom looks evenly at her son, seated opposite her in this small living room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: What's involved?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN
{DIALOGUE}: Well.
{DIALOGUE}: It's a great opportunity.
{DIALOGUE}: He'll be well-paid, and published nationally --
{META_DATA}: (quickly)
{DIALOGUE}: -- and he'll go on tour with a rock band for four days.
{DIALOGUE}: No small planes... he travels on a bus.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Is it time for me to say something?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN
{DIALOGUE}: Sure.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN
{DIALOGUE}: And in anticipation of that response -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN
{DIALOGUE}: -- William has prepared --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (rueful)
{DIALOGUE}: "Lo, that which I have feared has come upon me."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (lightening fast)
{DIALOGUE}: "He who jealously guards his fears, quietly yearns to bring them about!"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mrs. Deegan admires their high-strung intellectual parrying, makes an impressed noise.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (with compassion)
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: I have raised him to be an honor student, which he is.
{DIALOGUE}: We have agreed on all our goals.
{DIALOGUE}: We raised him to be a lawyer, we moved here to be near the finest law school in the West.
{DIALOGUE}: Plus, he has finals coming up, and in one week he graduates with all his friends -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DARRYL
{DIALOGUE}: He's got no friends!!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Darryl.
{DIALOGUE}: Please.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby, having anticipated all of the above, William nods to Mrs. Deegan, and stands.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. DEEGAN
{DIALOGUE}: Elaine, may I present to you... your own son.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William takes a lawyerly stroll, turns to face his mom.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Lady of the Jury.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I wish to disprove the prevailing false belief that rock music is based on drugs and sex.
{DIALOGUE}: True, perhaps at one time... but rock music is different now.
{DIALOGUE}: It is now performed by hard-working intellectuals, with... with blazing intellectual pursuits, and I am going to play for you a piece of music designed to show you that my thesis is correct.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: This is going to be hell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Across the room, Darryl takes his position near the stereo.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: The song is based on the literature of Tolkien... and it's mystical attempt to elevate humanity has been successful throughout the world... this song will change your life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom stifles a cough.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William nods to Darryl, who reverentially drops the needle with a thud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom is trapped, as we listen to silent static... and then... the opening notes of Led Zeppelin's "Stairway to Heaven."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William gives his Mother the album cover's inner-sleeve with lyrics.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: We ask you only to listen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera passes across their serious and expectant faces.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The intro in not short.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We listen, just watching their faces, as Elaine becomes increasingly impatient.
{DIALOGUE}: ELAINE				WILLIAM When is it going to start - Soon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Immediately, overlapping, the vocal begins.
{META_DATA}: ("There's a lady who's sure all that glitters is gold.")
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 48 SUN MOVING SLOWLY ACROSS THE SKY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sprinklers click across the lawns.
{META_DATA}: ("... and it makes me wonder... ")
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 49 INT. LIVING ROOM -- AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom adjust herself in the chair, listens politely, checks her watch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks at William.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 50 EXT. HOME - AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sprinklers continue.
{META_DATA}: ("If there's a bustle in your hedgerow... ")
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 51 INT. LIVING ROOM -- AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom listens fitfully.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The song continues.
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 52 EXT. HOUSE -- STILL LATER AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sprinklers shut off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music is now blasting.
{META_DATA}: ("To be a rock, and not to roll... ")
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 53 INT. LIVING ROOM - LATER AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom's face remains stoic to the bitter end.
{META_DATA}: ("... and she's buying the Stairway to Heaven.")
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The song ends.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All look to Elaine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They wait on her response.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear the turntable arm return to its cradle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: What am I supposed to say?
{DIALOGUE}: You say it's Tolkien, fine.
{DIALOGUE}: They sound like nice kids.
{DIALOGUE}: Is it meant to elevate humanity?
{DIALOGUE}: "Sure, let's elevate humanity.
{DIALOGUE}: After we sell you drugs and sex."
{DIALOGUE}: All I have is my honesty.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what I believe, and that's what I know.
{META_DATA}: (flipping through magazine)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh.
{DIALOGUE}: Here's a nice ad.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She holds up the magazine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And ad reads, in large bold type: BUY THIS FUCKING ALBUM.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: You've clearly ganged up on me, and I still say no.
{DIALOGUE}: No no no no no no no.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She shuts her eyes, and blurts out something against her better judgement.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: NO MORE THAN FOUR DAYS AND I WANT A PHONE NUMBER FOR WHERE YOU ARE EVERY MINUTE AND I WANT YOU TO CALL ME TWICE A DAY AND YOU'D BETTER NOT MISS ONE TEST - AND NO DRUGS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William nods gratefully, and exits frame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hold on the empty chair, as drums herald the beginning of the Allman Brothers Band's "Trouble No More" from Live at Fillmore East.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SHOT MOVES IN ON ELAINE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: who feels a very particular kind of loneliness.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the loneliness she got married, and then raised a family, to escape.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 54 INT. STILLWATER TOUR BUS -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An empty Heineken beer bottle rolls up and down the aisle, taking us to William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William picks up the bottle and places it in the seat back pocket in front of him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has joined the circus, and the feeling of being here is a lot more lonely and forbidding than he expected.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bus struggles to make it up the hill, back rows shuddering loudly, as music continues.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: C'mon, Doris!
{DIALOGUE}: Darling Bus.
{DIALOGUE}: You can make it!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 55 EXT. NEVADA DESERT HIGHWAY -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Stillwater Tour Bus rumbles down the desert highway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The destination banner reads - ALMOST FAMOUS -- TOUR 73.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music continues.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 56 INT. BUS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William strains for a look at Russell five rows up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He plays slide guitar, working out a part.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Next to Russell is Penny Lane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny raises an early-model Polaroid camera and - flash - takes a picture of a nearby sleeping Jeff Bebe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Gotcha.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff grumbles from the depths of a hangover.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny stuffs the shot in her pocket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches, his private heart pounds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Polexia appears and sits next to him, noticing his shyness.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{DIALOGUE}: Do you have any pot?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a journalist.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{DIALOGUE}: Well, go do your job then.
{DIALOGUE}: You're on the road, man.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all happening!
{DIALOGUE}: Get in there.
{DIALOGUE}: Go talk to 'em!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Challenged, William rises and approaches Russell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He fixes the charismatic guitarist in his sights.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shot takes him down the aisle to the jamming star guitarist.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He crouches in the aisle and talks to Russell who immediately seems moody.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His mood is in the air.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (very professional)
{DIALOGUE}: Russell.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you think we might be able to find some time to talk when we get to Phoenix?
{DIALOGUE}: I want to interview everyone separately... and I felt we'd start with you and me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby, Jeff now listens in, feeling immediately jealous.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Absolutely.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell turns away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid squats uncomfortably in the aisle, babbling on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Because I've got a thing in a couple days.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: What.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (self-conscious)
{DIALOGUE}: It's a..
{DIALOGUE}: thing where... uhm... you go there to graduate.
{DIALOGUE}: School.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (sharply)
{DIALOGUE}: I never graduated.
{DIALOGUE}: And look what happened.
{DIALOGUE}: You're here interviewing me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Good point.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Laughs from everybody listening nearby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a good line.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William makes a quick jot in his notebook.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: No no no.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't put that in Rolling Stone.
{DIALOGUE}: My bio says I graduated.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll come up with something better later.
{DIALOGUE}: Just enjoy the ride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell eyes the notebook suspiciously before turning away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny notices William's discomfort, laughing warmly, all while grabbing a Coke and giving one to nearby bassist Larry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LARRY
{DIALOGUE}: How did you know I was thirsty?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He didn't even realize he was thirsty, but he is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He nods thanks to Penny, the perfect road companion for all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then Penny gives the other Coke, her Coke, to William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He accepts it too, and starts back to his seat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's been blown off, and he knows it, but before he exits Penny grabs his arm and whispers in his ear:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I may need to stay in your room tonight.
{DIALOGUE}: Russell's in a bad mood.
{DIALOGUE}: He's very Bob Dylan in Don't Look Back today.
{DIALOGUE}: He's trying to write.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William nods cooly -- they are comrades -- and returns to his seat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A large joint passes in front of him, across him, to Polexia, as everyone cheers Doris the Bus rumbling up another hill.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{META_DATA}: (inhaling deeply)
{DIALOGUE}: Want some?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: No thanks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A wall of pot smoke is exhaled, right into his face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It surrounds him like a cloud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bus shudders, as Russell continues playing slide up ahead.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 57 INT. WILLIAM'S LIVING ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine sits in her living room, filled with her books.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Large Department store photos of her children on the wall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She feels her own loneliness, and his too, as she dials a phone number.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Has William Miller arrived yet?
{DIALOGUE}: He hasn't.
{DIALOGUE}: Could you give him a message as soon as you see him?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 58 INT. BUS -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Several hours later on this ride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Outside, night and desert.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Inside, a few cigarettes, a joint of two glow in the darkness of the bus.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The end of the Led Zeppelin classic "Whole Lotta Love" plays from the bus stereo, full blast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everybody is free and anonymous in the dark.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They sing at full-volume.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William looks out the window in wonder.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZEPPELIN/ALL
{DIALOGUE}: "Way down inside... (woman) woman... you need... "
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The ten-ton guitar chord of Jimmy Page.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZEPPELIN/ALL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: "Loooooooooooooooooooooooovvve... "
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: John Bonham's drums thunder through the bus, everybody still singing as they dip down into the city ahead, Phoenix.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches the living documentary around him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He writes furiously in the green notebook, scribbling in the dark, trying to steady his writing on the bumpy bus.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind him, someone is beating along to the song on his seat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He never want to leave this world.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 59 INT. ARIZONA RAMADA INN LOBBY -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All enter the lobby like warriors, in a pack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The hotel chairs are spotted with curious hangers-on, decked out and lounging.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick is already stationed, as always, at the front desk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sad state of hotel service grates on a road dog like Dick.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is forever teaching others their jobs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Jeff, Tony... Keys... keys... keys... room list...
{META_DATA}: (re: luggage, to hotel bellman)
{DIALOGUE}: If it doesn't have a number on it, it ain't ours!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gives key and a stack of messages to Russell, and turns to William who he makes feel more important.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny is nearby with her suitcase and tackle box purse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches Russell's guitars whisked away - they are luggage-numbered 1, 3, and 4.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: The Enemy!
{DIALOGUE}: Here you go, here's the key to your palatial suite, room list, plus let me give you a luggage tag.
{DIALOGUE}: You're Number 42.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLERK
{DIALOGUE}: Is this Mr. Miller?
{DIALOGUE}: You have a message from Elaine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLERK
{META_DATA}: (confidentially)
{DIALOGUE}: She's a handful.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William cooly takes the folded message, doesn't look at it, and tries to pretend this embarrassing moment didn't happen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff exchanges a look with Russell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby, the walking commotion arrives, clacking through the lobby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's Sapphire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Last night's clothes are now today's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She holds a travel case, and hanger with some odd blouses.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: Finally, you're here!!
{DIALOGUE}: They kicked me out of my room!
{DIALOGUE}: Fuck Ozzy!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hugs Penny Lane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Estrella appears, happy to have help with Sapphire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON RUSSELL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: who approaches William.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Come by in a few minutes.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll do the interview.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid exits and goes to join Penny, who is still comforting Sapphire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell looks through his messages.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The guitar, now in a case, never leaves his hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff Bebe approaches, regarding William standing with Penny and the girls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Intrigue is swirling in the lobby.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: I'm worried, man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Naw, we can trust him.
{DIALOGUE}: He's a fan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: But it's Rolling Stone.
{DIALOGUE}: He looks harmless, but he does represent the magazine that trashed Eric Clapton, broke up Cream, ripped Led Zeppelin, and wrote that lame story about the Allman Brothers Band that bummed Duane out before he died.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't forget the Rules.
{DIALOGUE}: This little shit is the Enemy.
{DIALOGUE}: He writes what he sees.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: But it would be cool to be on the cover.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Leave it to me.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll get a good story.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Plus our girlfriends read this magazine and -
{META_DATA}: (looking at Band-aids)
{DIALOGUE}: -- you know.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: You made your point.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll take to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON WILLIAM BY ELEVATOR
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny speaks confidentially to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: If she is slightly bossy, it is only because she's good at logistics, emotional and otherwise.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Can Sapphire stay in your room tonight?
{DIALOGUE}: She had a big fight with Ozzy, and Polexia's not working out with Jeff Bebe.
{META_DATA}: (to Sapphire and Polexia)
{DIALOGUE}: You just have to remember... these guys are jealous, insecure, talented, egocentric, and manipulative geniuses... they're lead-singers.
{DIALOGUE}: They can say "I love you" to 20,000 people... but any fewer is a real problem.
{META_DATA}: (girls nod, comforted, she continues to the kid)
{DIALOGUE}: Jeff Bebe has so much jealousy over Russell that he can't express.
{DIALOGUE}: Plus, he never slept last night.
{DIALOGUE}: You keep Sapphire and I'll stay with Russell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William covers his disappointment over losing Penny as a roommate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cooly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Sure.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll take her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{DIALOGUE}: Me too?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Sure.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Estrella arrives with travel bag, equally homeless, looking hopeful.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: If there's room -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny squeezes him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He feels cool... but the girl he really wanted to stay in his room now joins Russell, disappearing into the elevator.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks down at the message in his hand, and opens it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It reads: DON'T TAKE DRUGS!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He snaps it closed quickly, before anyone can see.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 59A IN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: RUSSELL's ROOM -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell plays acoustic guitar, a notebook cradled on his lap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Trying to write.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's coming slowly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shot moves off him, past a flickering television, onto Penny who silently and intently watches Russell as if he's a rare and beautiful bird.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks over at her - she turns away quickly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He goes back to work.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tries to catch her watching him again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She turns away just in time.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 60 INT. WILLIAM'S HOTEL ROOM -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stillwater's "Fever Dog" plays from the t.v. radio.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William on the bed, a thick local phone book on his lap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His hotel room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He watches self-consciously as the girls go about the ritual of inhabiting a room on the road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sapphire flutters a paisley scarf over the room lamp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Polexia puts a towel along the crack of the door, blows out the glowing embers on too- many sticks of incense, and moves to the phone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Estrella has joined them as well, complete with a bag full of shoes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Instantly, we have atmosphere and not much room left in this, the smallest room in the hotel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William thumbs through the phone book with fascination.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: All these people.
{META_DATA}: (wondrous, off phone book)
{DIALOGUE}: And they all live in Phoenix.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: Hi Dad!!
{DIALOGUE}: I can't talk long!
{DIALOGUE}: I'm here in Paris.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm staying in another Youth Hostel with no phone and no address for mail!!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (still wondrous, from phone book)
{DIALOGUE}: Alex. Lowbatz.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{META_DATA}: (emerging from bathroom)
{DIALOGUE}: I was the one who told him what to tattoo on his fingers, I was the one who made his shirts... I was there when his wife left him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Charles.
{DIALOGUE}: C. Swoop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{META_DATA}: (on phone)
{DIALOGUE}: I CAN SEE THE EIFFELL TOWER.
{DIALOGUE}: DO YOU KNOW THERE ARE 578 STEPS TO THE TOP?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She's reading from a European tour book.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Paul and Debbie Finger.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{META_DATA}: (looking out window)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh my God.
{DIALOGUE}: Simon Kirke of Bad Company is by the pool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The girls mobilize by the window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William is increasingly aware that he is an outsider in his own tiny room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He tries to organize his stuff in the corner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{DIALOGUE}: I GOTTA GO!
{DIALOGUE}: I'LL CALL FROM ROME!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: Is anybody here as worried about Penny and Russell as I am?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLEXIA
{META_DATA}: (the perfect daughter)
{DIALOGUE}: AND HAPPY BIRTHDAY TO MAGGIE!!
{DIALOGUE}: I LOVE YOU!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She winks at William, who looks away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{META_DATA}: (to Polexia and William)
{DIALOGUE}: Ooo, watch out - whoever you look at when you say that - that's who you really mean.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Polexia hands up and throws a pillow at Sapphire, the kid watches these girls like a tennis match.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 60A IN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PENNY AND RUSSELL'S ROOM - SAME TIME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell puts down his guitar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: You know.
{DIALOGUE}: We should talk about what we don't talk about.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: We don't have to.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: No, I - I went to Catholic school.
{DIALOGUE}: I believe in guilt and... you know, if there's any to be had, I pretty much want to roll around in it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I don't believe in attachments.
{DIALOGUE}: No boundaries.
{DIALOGUE}: Just the music.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just saying, it's okay to talk about it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny stands and turns.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She speaks the word.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The name is out in the open.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{DIALOGUE}: Leslie.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (somehow satisfied)
{DIALOGUE}: Alright - now we're talking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But she continues, saying the name in a multitude of different ways, in different accents, and with different degrees of indifference and passion and lust and play-acting and mock- drama.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PUSH IN ON HIS FACE
