{DIALOGUE}: Hello?
{META_DATA}: INTERCUT:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WILLIAM'S HOUSE -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's Mom on the phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (measured, very proper)
{DIALOGUE}: May I speak with William please?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{META_DATA}: (cheerfully)
{DIALOGUE}: He's not here.
{DIALOGUE}: I think he's in the bar with the Band.
{DIALOGUE}: They just got back from the radio station.
{DIALOGUE}: Is this Maryann with the pot?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: No this isn't Maryann with the pot.
{DIALOGUE}: This is Elaine... his Mother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Estrella physically recoils.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{META_DATA}: (cringing)
{DIALOGUE}: I thought you were English.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: Could you please give him a message?
{DIALOGUE}: Could you tell him to call home immediately?
{DIALOGUE}: And could you also tell him -
{META_DATA}: (at full power)
{DIALOGUE}: I know what's going on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: Alright.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: But I'm just going to say this, and I'm going to stand by it.
{META_DATA}: (can't help herself)
{DIALOGUE}: You should be really proud of him.
{DIALOGUE}: 'Cause I know guys... and I'll bet you do too.
{DIALOGUE}: And he respects women, and he likes women, and let's just pause and appreciate a man like that.
{DIALOGUE}: You created him out of thin air, and you raised him right, and we're all looking out for him.
{DIALOGUE}: And that's more than I've ever said to my own parents, so there you go.
{META_DATA}: (silence)
{DIALOGUE}: This is the maid speaking, by the way.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 68 INT. HOTEL LOBBY -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell and William sit in two large red-leatherette seats in the hotel lobby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William shuffles through many pages of questions written in small script.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His tape recorder microphone sits balanced on the chair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (very professional)
{DIALOGUE}: Now that you're starting to be successful, you had twenty-six years to write your first Album... and you'll have maybe four months for the second.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you worry that the pressure of the business will get in the way of the original joy of making your music?
{DIALOGUE}: Or -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell blinks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The all-consuming issues of his life are right in front of him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Whoa!
{META_DATA}: (laughing)
{DIALOGUE}: I need three more beers and my guitar before I can answer that question.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's take a walk.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 69 EXT. HOTEL POOL AREA - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell walks the outskirts of the pool area with William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William follows him through the sliding glass door to his room, facing the pool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell grabs his guitar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They stand for a moment, unheard by the others, and regard the living portrait twenty yards in front of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The off-limits after-hours pool area has been overtaken by the Stillwater tour members.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff Bebe sits in a chair nearby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick laughs at a joke.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Always the life of the party, Penny Lane dispenses stolen towels from a maid cart.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And she is the first to slip into the pool for some after-hours, against-the-rules swimming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Effortlessly, she turns a collection of people into a party.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They regard her, well out of earshot of the others.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: For a minute I thought you were actually a real journalist... which is... you know, it's great.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Shut that thing off, and I'll tell you the truth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William shuts his tape recorder off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: It's off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Look.
{DIALOGUE}: I trust you.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to lay this right on you.
{DIALOGUE}: Just make us look cool.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I will quote you warmly and accurately.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: That's what I'm worried about.
{DIALOGUE}: See - some of us have girlfriends back home.
{DIALOGUE}: Some of us have wives.
{DIALOGUE}: And... some of the people you meet on the road are really amazing people...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They both watch Penny Lane, sparkling, fresh from the pool.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She places hotel furniture into the shallow end and inviting all, even other curious hotel guests, to join them in the pool.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Like you.
{DIALOGUE}: And some of the things that happen are good for just a few people to know about - as opposed to, say, a million people.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dawn is breaking for William.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Ohhhh.
{DIALOGUE}: Oh.
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: You know what I mean?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: See, you're dangerous.
{DIALOGUE}: Most people are just waiting to talk, but you listen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: So your question you asked me.
{DIALOGUE}: I think about It every fucking night.
{DIALOGUE}: The "business."
{DIALOGUE}: I hate it!
{META_DATA}: (quietly)
{DIALOGUE}: I grew up with these guys, okay?
{DIALOGUE}: I can't play all that I can play, I'm past these musicians, do you understand?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: The more popular we get, the more I can't walk on them, the bigger their houses get, the more pressure... you forget, man.
{DIALOGUE}: You forget what it was like to be real, to be a fan.
{DIALOGUE}: You can hear it in a lot of bands who've been successful - it doesn't sound like music anymore.
{DIALOGUE}: It sounds like... like lifestyle maintenance.
{META_DATA}: (suddenly confessional)
{DIALOGUE}: I used to be able to hear the sounds of the world.
{DIALOGUE}: Everything, to me, used to sound like music.
{DIALOGUE}: Everything.
{DIALOGUE}: Now I don't hear it.
{DIALOGUE}: You know what I'm trying to say?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (ruefully)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Man, it feels good to say this stuff out loud.
{DIALOGUE}: But what am I doing?
{DIALOGUE}: I'm telling secrets to the one guy you don't tell secrets to.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (feeling included)
{DIALOGUE}: No, that's okay.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll do the interview tomorrow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: This is good.
{DIALOGUE}: So there's the "friend" and then there's the "interview guy."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: So tonight it's "friend"....
{DIALOGUE}: and when we wake up tomorrow - "interview guy."
{DIALOGUE}: We'll figure it out as we go, buddy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Hey - for whatever it's worth - you guys are really good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell laughs at the kid's easy naivete.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hands his guitar to the kid, and joins the party.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches, part of the crowd... somehow feeling a little compromised.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He doesn't care.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny gestures for him to join them.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 70 EXT. SUN STADIUM - AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William interviews Larry in the seats of the empty arena.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On stage, Ed soundchecks his drums.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: How would you describe your role in Stillwater?
{DIALOGUE}: What is the chemical that you add to the chemistry?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LARRY
{DIALOGUE}: I'm the bass-player.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{META_DATA}: (pressing for some poetry)
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{DIALOGUE}: And when you take that away... what would be missing?
{DIALOGUE}: Stylistically?
{DIALOGUE}: What chemical?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LARRY
{META_DATA}: (not getting it)
{DIALOGUE}: The bass?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Larry doesn't give him much.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 71 EXT. SUN STADIUM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's raining.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The pre-show huddle breaks up, William a part of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny Lane adjusts Larry's look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She takes the scarf from around his neck and ties it around his leg.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks instantly better.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches in the darkness as Dick takes the microphone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The best part of his day has arrived.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In his important voice:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Good evening Phoenix.
{META_DATA}: (applause)
{DIALOGUE}: From Troy, Michigan.
{DIALOGUE}: Please welcome, Stillwater.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lights come up, as the band launches into "Fever Dog."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff begins singing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell reaches to adjust the microphone for a back-up vocal and is hit with something unexpected.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A sharp electrical shock.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's just a slight pop in the loud din of music, but within a moment something is clearly wrong.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell holds onto the microphone stand with a surprised look, conducting high-voltage for two seconds and then he snaps his hand off the metal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His face is white, he takes off his guitar and walks off-stage, collapsing a couple steps later.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 72 EXT. BACKSTAGE -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick is waving wildly for the band to board the bus, which has been pulled up into the backstage area.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He guides a sagging Russell, assisted by Penny Lane, into the bus.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Get in, get in!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William boards the bus, as the extremely agitated PROMOTER arrives to confront Dick.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROMOTER
{DIALOGUE}: Are you the manager of this band?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: That, and more.
{DIALOGUE}: Get in!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROMOTER
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't even play a full set!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick whirls and unleashes an anger we've not yet seen, gesturing with the silver briefcase that does not leave his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Your shoddy stage set-up almost killed our guitarist!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROMOTER
{DIALOGUE}: You trashed the dressing room - you didn't play your thirty-five minutes.
{DIALOGUE}: You didn't fulfill your contract -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Everybody in!
{DIALOGUE}: Get in the bus!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROMOTER
{DIALOGUE}: I'll report you to every promoter in the country!
{DIALOGUE}: I'm gonna talk to Frank Barcelona!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: YOU DON'T FUCK WITH MY BAND'S SAFETY!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROMOTER
{DIALOGUE}: I hope you have a good lawyer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: I AM A LAWYER!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He swings into the bus, as the bus revs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PROMOTER
{DIALOGUE}: LOCK THE GATE ON 'EM!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 73 INT. BUS -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell sits, pale, next to Penny at the front of the bus.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He examines his singed hand, shaking it a little to emphasize the positivity of her words.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Don't worry.
{DIALOGUE}: It's happened to all the greats.
{DIALOGUE}: Thank God you didn't hold the mike stand with both hands, you'd still be holding it.
{DIALOGUE}: This is a good thing.
{DIALOGUE}: It's a good, good, good thing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William sits nearby, watching Russell, making notes out of eye- sight of others.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The ever-wary Jeff, unseen by William, cranes to see that he's writing in his notebook.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick swings into the seat across from Russell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bus door shuts, as the promoter is still yelling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Doris is slow to gain speed, as Estrella appears, running alongside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She knocks on the window next to William.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ESTRELLA
{DIALOGUE}: I forgot to tell you!
{DIALOGUE}: Your mom says to call home immediately.
{DIALOGUE}: She says she knows what's going on!
{META_DATA}: (receding)
{DIALOGUE}: See you guys in Topeka!
{DIALOGUE}: I'll catch a ride with Sabbath!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William nods with embarrassment, waves to her, as the bus races toward the now closing gate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{META_DATA}: (casually, to Russell)
{DIALOGUE}: Wanna buy a gate?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Before Russell can answer - BASH.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Doris barrels through the steel-gate, snapping it like a chopstick to great cheers inside this bus.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: You just bought a gate.
{META_DATA}: (to the bus)
{DIALOGUE}: C'mon Doris!!
{DIALOGUE}: Get us out of town!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bus struggles up a slight incline, everybody rooting for Doris, as she eases out of the parking lot and onto a thoroughfare.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: What did it feel like to be electrocuted?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: It burns.
{DIALOGUE}: It feels like a dose of lead shooting through your body... and then you see God, and he says, "How bad do you want to be legendary?"
{DIALOGUE}: And god damnit.
{DIALOGUE}: I let go.
{META_DATA}: (shaky grin as all laugh warmly)
{DIALOGUE}: Rock and roll.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff watches this charisma with thinly veiled envy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid scribbles in his notebook.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear Led Zeppelin's "That's the Way."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 74 INT. BUS - EARLY MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Song continues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Almost everybody is asleep.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William takes the camera and snaps a Polaroid of a sleeping Penny.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She wakes up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: Give that to me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She grabs for it, they have a brief play-fight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He grabs some other Polaroids from her pocket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hustles to the back of the bus, pockets the photo, and settles down to watch the passing landscapes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She chases him down the aisle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music continues as she sits down next to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Out the window, a long-distance running team of Girls keeps pace with the bus for a bit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They wave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny watches them over sunglasses, waves briefly to the real world.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY (cont'd)
{META_DATA}: (breathing heavy, owning the world)
{DIALOGUE}: When we go to Morocco, I think we should wear completely different clothes, and be completely different people.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: What will our names be?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She snaps a Polaroid of a nearby sleeping Silent Ed, pockets the Polaroid.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She regards Russell up ahead, also sleeping.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her attention has already wandered from Morocco.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: What do you think of Russell?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I like him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: You're coming to Cleveland, right?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Cleveland, Ohio?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh no no no.
{DIALOGUE}: I gotta get my interview with Russell before Greenville.
{DIALOGUE}: And you've got to help me.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay?
{DIALOGUE}: Friends... remember?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny is still watching Russell.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: You should give him a break.
{DIALOGUE}: There are real problems in the band.
{DIALOGUE}: Off the record.
