{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is an eloquent moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He thinks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shrugs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid tumbles with more questions.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: These interviews are not going well.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 76 INT. BATHROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William, looking concerned over the state of his interviews, walks into the backstage bathroom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He makes a few surreptitious notes in his notebook before noticing that Jeff is standing there, clearly just finishing a quick hit of cocaine offered by a Local Hanger-On.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seeing the kid, he immediately hides the coke spoon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Hey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Hey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William pretends he sees nothing as he turns to the urinal, and shot stays on Jeff, who looks a little high and a little worried.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 77 INT. BACKSTAGE PAY PHONE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William is on the pay phone with his Mother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The show booms in the background.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{DIALOGUE}: Mom.
{DIALOGUE}: Mom... Mom.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 78 INT. STAGE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stillwater on-stage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A great show.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell on fire.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 79 INT. BACKSTAGE PAY PHONE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William on the phone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Estrella leans on him, fixing her shoe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Right now -- Topeka.
{DIALOGUE}: Then Greenville.
{DIALOGUE}: Then home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He winces slightly, holds the phone away from his ear for a moment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry I didn't call yesterday!
{DIALOGUE}: It's not like you can just carry a phone around with you.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 80 INT. ELAINE'S SCHOOL OFFICE -- AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom sits in her school office, a miniature version of her home - a fortress in which she is surrounded by books.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sun is going down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She can't resist a sentimental moment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: I guess I just miss you, and I don't understand why I've driven both my kids so far away from me.
{DIALOGUE}: By all practical rules don't I get you for three more years?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is touched by her vulnerability, more visible now than ever, as music continues in b.g.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Was I not fun?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 81 INT. BACKSTAGE PAY PHONE -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William has his finger in his ear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The din if Stillwater's set now blots out all other noise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is not the time to answer this question.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I missed the last thing you said.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom takes a pause.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: I LOVE YOU.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny now enters, watching.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: WHAT?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{META_DATA}: (angry, louder)
{DIALOGUE}: I MISS YOU AND I LOVE YOU!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William now notices Penny standing nearby, picking at a salad from a paper dish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking at her, he lets loose with what he believes is a private confession.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: I LOVE YOU!!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny smiles knowingly, collecting his affection like another backstage pass, and turns away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera stays on William.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is suddenly and deeply embarrassed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's just told her that he loves her and she knows it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hangs up, traumatized.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 82 INT. TOPEKA DRESSING ROOM -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell's hair is slicked with sweat from a show just finished.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is shirtless with a towel around his shoulders.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Luggage for the next city is stacked by the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Fire away.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm ready.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm on the "You" Train.
{DIALOGUE}: Take me there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid plugs in his microphone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell listens as he springs his first question.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Do you have to be depressed to write a sad song?
{DIALOGUE}: Do you have to be in love to write a love song?
{DIALOGUE}: Is a song better if it really happened to you?
{DIALOGUE}: Like, "If You Say Nothing"... where did you write that and how did it come about?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell admires the many questions.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Says nothing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at his hand, thinks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: When did you get so professional?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the background, Penny Lane irons Silent Ed's shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Grinning, she cuffs his shoulder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: To the shirtless silent drummer, waiting for his shirt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PENNY
{DIALOGUE}: I'm almost done with my shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ed watches her appreciatively, drumming silently on a rubber pad.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny kisses Russell, who swings her onto his lap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the corner, Jeff watches them all with a vague feeling of being underappreciated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And now Dick enters with a large cardboard box.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Russell, your dad showed up again.
{DIALOGUE}: And on a lighter note.
{META_DATA}: (importantly)
{DIALOGUE}: Gentlemen.
{DIALOGUE}: Your first t-shirts have arrived.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is an immediate buzz in the room, as Dick yanks open the box filled with new white t-shirts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He untangles the first fresh shirt, and displays it proudly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A silent beat as all examine it - their first t-shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Faces fall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ed stops drumming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There has been a mistake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a fuzzy band photo with the group name emblazoned below.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Only Russell, who stand out front, is colored- in and emphasized on the shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns away, making a noise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jeff stares at the t-shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's just about in tears.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a long silence and then... Ed resumes drumming on the rubber pad.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: It's the record company's mistake.
{DIALOGUE}: And they will pay.
{DIALOGUE}: Shirts gone, band happy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He drops the offending shirt into the trash, as if it were contaminated, and exits with the box.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches as the two men, Russell and Jeff, move to opposite sides of the room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell puts on a shirt, so does Jeff.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The vibe is thick.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russel turns to see Jeff staring at him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Can we just skip the vibe and go straight to us laughing about this?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{META_DATA}: (bitterly)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (trying for a joke)
{DIALOGUE}: Because I can see by your face - you want to get into this -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: How can you tell?
{DIALOGUE}: I'm just one of the out-of-focus guys.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Here we go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches as Russell fishes the t-shirt out of the trash.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Here.
{DIALOGUE}: Take it.
{DIALOGUE}: You LOVE this shirt - it lets you say everything you want to say.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Well, it speaks pretty loudly to me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: It's a t-shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell turns away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: I'm always gonna tell you the truth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Are you doing coke again?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Oh yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: All the time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid looks down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: This is big stuff, man.
{DIALOGUE}: From the very beginning -- we said -- I'm the front man and you're the guitarist with mystique.
{DIALOGUE}: That's the dynamic we agreed on -- Page, Plant... Mick, Keith.
{DIALOGUE}: But somehow it's all turning around.
{DIALOGUE}: We have got to control what's happening to us.
{DIALOGUE}: There's a responsibility here -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Excuse me, but didn't we all get into this to avoid responsibility?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Forgive me.
{META_DATA}: (continuing, on shirt)
{DIALOGUE}: But this is the slow-moving train of compromise that will kill us.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell makes a disgusted noise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny Lane exits discreetly, looking back at William.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: I can't say anymore with a writer here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: You can trust him, you can say whatever you want.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{META_DATA}: (eyes suddenly moist)
{DIALOGUE}: I works as hard or harder than anybody on that stage.
{DIALOGUE}: You know what I do - I connect.
{DIALOGUE}: I get people off.
{DIALOGUE}: I look for the guy who isn't getting off, and I make him get off.
{META_DATA}: (beat)
{DIALOGUE}: Actually, that you can print.
{META_DATA}: (continues to Russell)
{DIALOGUE}: And yet, why do I always end up feeling like I'm a joke to you?
{DIALOGUE}: I feel nothing but love for you.
{DIALOGUE}: We're a family.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at the t-shirt and starts to cry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Embarrassed, he grows angrier.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: You want to pretend this isn't going to be a very big band.
{DIALOGUE}: Well it is.
{DIALOGUE}: You call yourself a leader of this band, but your direction allowed the t-shirt, when you allowed Dick to manage us, 'cause he's your friend... don't you see?
{DIALOGUE}: The t-shirt is everything.
{DIALOGUE}: It's everything.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Is it my turn?
{DIALOGUE}: Because I think we should, for once, say what we really mean.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, this is the part where you quit -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (stiffening)
{DIALOGUE}: Right.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm so predictable.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: No I gotta tell the truth -- I want you to like me.
{DIALOGUE}: But sometimes I feel like you collect people who love you and then very skillfully... you make them feel bad that they're not good enough for you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Stick to singing, brother, 'cause you ain't gonna make it as a shrink.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Deal with it!
{DIALOGUE}: And let me just say what nobody Else wants to say to you -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JEFF
{DIALOGUE}: Your looks have become a problem.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 82A EXT. BACKSTAGE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell walks swiftly past a happy silver-haired man, who holds court with beer in hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He dresses too young for his age, late fifties.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is DAD.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DAD
{DIALOGUE}: Son!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (dutifully)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello Harry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dad introduces a woman much younger, who eyes Russell hungrily.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DAD
{DIALOGUE}: He got all the good genes, huh?
{DIALOGUE}: Meet Deirdre.
{DIALOGUE}: We're getting married in July.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 83 EXT. ARENA -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell walks fast outside the arena.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William hustles to catch up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two men walk in long silent strides in the cold night air, beyond the backstage area.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fans begin to recognize and follow at a discreet distance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: You okay?
{DIALOGUE}: You alright?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell doesn't answer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
