{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOMEONE'S VOICE
{DIALOGUE}: He's just some fan... what did you expect?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William sits there, as only David Felton stay behind, brandishing his cigarette-holder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sits down next to the kid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FELTON
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I believe you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at the kid, decides to offer a personal parable.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FELTON (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Jim Morrison once came to my house and drank a beer.
{DIALOGUE}: The beer is still on my mantle.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm 35 years old with Jim Morrison's beer as a shrine.
{DIALOGUE}: I wanted to be Earnest Hemingway.
{DIALOGUE}: Instead.
{DIALOGUE}: I have Jim Morrison's beer.
{META_DATA}: (shrugs, he's learned to live with it)
{DIALOGUE}: If you didn't make your story up, good for you.
{DIALOGUE}: If you did make it up... good for you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid looks at him, too tired and still in shock.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FELTON (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Say something, so I know you're alive.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Goodbye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He exits.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FELTON
{DIALOGUE}: Powerful word.
{DIALOGUE}: Strong.
{DIALOGUE}: Final.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 157 INT. BACKSTAGE CREW MEAL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell Hammond sits down on a plastic chair with a paper-plate filled with buffet-style food - steak and baked potato.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Preoccupied, and several seats away from other crew members.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He drinks a glass of milk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Out old friend Sapphire takes the seat next to him, holding a skimpy paper plate of vegetables.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: I feel bad.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, at least you feel.
{DIALOGUE}: That puts you in a higher class of asshole.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They eat in silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sapphire looks around.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The new breed of groupies eye her, as they cruise Russell on the periphery.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're bolder, flashier.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She eyes them back with seniority.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: What did I do?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: Well - you can do what the big boys do.
{META_DATA}: (he looks at her)
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The girls still circle Russell nearby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's unaware.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: You believe these new girls?
{DIALOGUE}: None of 'em take birth control, and they eat all the steak.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks sadly at her plate of vegetables.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An ever-sharp mind in last night's clothes, she commands Russell's respect.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: They don't even know what it id to be a fan!
{DIALOGUE}: To blindly love some silly piece of music... or some band so much that it hurts... please, they're all just after the money.
{DIALOGUE}: Shoo --
{META_DATA}: (in their direction)
{DIALOGUE}: Go rob a bank!
{DIALOGUE}: It's more honest!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Is Penny okay?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: The Quaalude Incident.
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, it wasn't pretty.
{DIALOGUE}: She could have died.
{DIALOGUE}: I always warned her about letting too many guys fall in love with her.
{DIALOGUE}: I guess I was wrong.
{META_DATA}: (shrugs)
{DIALOGUE}: On of 'em saved her life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Well, it's finally over with Leslie.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to call her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: Let her retire.
{META_DATA}: (he doesn't respond)
{DIALOGUE}: You want to lock her up in a house in Michigan?
{DIALOGUE}: Please.
{META_DATA}: (he doesn't respond)
{DIALOGUE}: Write her a song someday.
{DIALOGUE}: She deserves it.
{DIALOGUE}: Something about that girl brought out the best in a lot of...
{META_DATA}: (looks around backstage)
{DIALOGUE}: ... pretty average people.
{DIALOGUE}: She deserves it...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell stares into his crew meal, nodding a little.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE (cont'd)
{META_DATA}: (forward thinking)
{DIALOGUE}: ... because something tells me twenty years from now, we'll remember her... and not much else.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell smiles to himself, knows it's true.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick passes, placing hands on Russell's shoulders, massaging a little.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DICK
{DIALOGUE}: Have a good vacation.
{DIALOGUE}: I hope the band stays together.
{DIALOGUE}: Before it all went down the shitter, it was starting to get really good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dick claps Russell on the back, and moves on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns to Sapphire.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not going to blame myself.
{DIALOGUE}: I do make people happy.
{DIALOGUE}: They just shouldn't get to know me... 'cause it appears to spoil everything.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: Don't be so easy on yourself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: What gives you the right to get this personal with me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAPPHIRE
{DIALOGUE}: Let's not reminisce.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 158 INT. SAN FRANCISCO AIRPORT -- NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William moves like a zombie through the airport, and collapses in a seat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sits still in the crowded flow of human traffic.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A cluster of Flight Attendants pass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One stops, a stylish young woman wearing a tall bubble-shaped PSA hat with swirling colors.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: William?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He feels like he's on Mars, and she looks like a Martian.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: You guys this is my brother!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MALE FLIGHT ATTENDANT
{META_DATA}: (ad if meeting a celebrity)
{DIALOGUE}: "The Narc?!"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William looks woefully at them, like a dog who's been hit by a car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: You guys, I'll deadhead back later.
{DIALOGUE}: I think I'm needed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MALE FLIGHT ATTENDANT
{DIALOGUE}: Nice to finally meet you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FEMALE ATTENDANT
{DIALOGUE}: You have a good day!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita looks in her brother's face.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: You look awful, but that's great.
{DIALOGUE}: You're living your life!
{DIALOGUE}: You're finally free of... her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: Hey.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll take off work.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's have an adventure together.
{DIALOGUE}: You and me, finally.
{DIALOGUE}: Anywhere you want to go.
{DIALOGUE}: Anywhere in the world.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 159 EXT. WILLIAM'S HOME -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William whistles the family whistle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sister and brother trudge up the steps.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: This is not my idea of a good time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WILLIAM
{DIALOGUE}: Just get me to my bed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{META_DATA}: (resigned)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll deal with her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William whistles again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom meets them at the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks at her trashed son who has finally come home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For the first time, she hugs Anita first, and it's not lost on Anita.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a clumsy neck-hug, neither wanting to commit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid passes to his Mother's left, with suitcase, intentionally nudging her into his sister.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita takes this as an aggressive act of love, and hugs her mother back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tears stream down Mom's face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their cheeks touch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom pulls away, and sees her own tears on Anita's face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Thinking that she's also crying, she grabs a tissue for them both.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 160 INT. ELAINE'S HOUSE -- CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The kid stands in the hallway listening, shaking his head, poised to enter his room, unseen by them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{META_DATA}: (so worried)
{DIALOGUE}: What are we going to do about him?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know.
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever happened to him, I just wish it could have happened to me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: The magazine killed his story.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now they really hug, Anita gulping back real tears.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches them bonding over the oddest thing - his failure.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William goes into the bedroom, the final three feet to sleep, and shuts the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A hand places a hotel sign on the door - DO NOT DISTURB.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slight push in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON BED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He collapses with all his clothes on, almost instantly asleep.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His walls, just as he left them, boast a pantheon of rock heroes... with a very lonely Abraham Lincoln (or Atticus Finch) in the center.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 161 INT. ROLLING STONE OFFICES -- DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The elevator doors ding open, and out walks Russell Hammond.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Secretary has just finished answering the phone, "Straight Arrow Publishers."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She puts the caller on hold.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, I'm Russel Hammond.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SECRETARY
{DIALOGUE}: You're here regarding?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: My life.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 162 INT. EDITORIAL OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell stands with the editors, observing the fine portraits on the walls.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's behind enemy lines, and he knows it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everything in the room fascinates him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: I don't care what happens.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't care if you put us on the cover.
{DIALOGUE}: But you sent us a kid and... and he was a fan.
{DIALOGUE}: And we all made friends with him - absolutely, to get a good story.
{DIALOGUE}: But then we actually liked him.
{DIALOGUE}: We thought he's... show us our lives in some mythic way and I guess... we're not mythic.
{DIALOGUE}: We panicked.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANN
{DIALOGUE}: You denied most of the story.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, well, here's the problem with the truth.
{DIALOGUE}: It's too true -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: Well, we appreciate the visit.
{DIALOGUE}: The last time an artist came here, it was Buddy Miles and he punched me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not punching anybody.
{DIALOGUE}: I am personally, as of 2 pm yesterday, on a voyage of self-reinvention.
{DIALOGUE}: This is about William Miller.
{META_DATA}: (counting off fingers)
{DIALOGUE}: He lives with us, he lost his virginity, he saw us at our worst, appreciated our best, he saved two lives, including mine... he smuggled about a half-pound of pot into Boston, and we never even told him -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearby, David Felton looks at another editor, raising an eyebrow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: -- we told him too much, we told him everything... He almost died with us over Tupelo... if the band survives him, it'll be a miracle... but you know, he tried to keep up, and that's a journalist to me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANN
{DIALOGUE}: It's too late.
{DIALOGUE}: We're going with a different cover.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{META_DATA}: (immediately)
{DIALOGUE}: Thank God.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Russell looks around at the numerous portraits if dead legendary rock stars, fixing on the one photo closest to all of them, a very vulnerable-looking Janis Joplin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A second thought.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: You tell me it's too late.
{DIALOGUE}: But I could go back to my hotel room and... and O.D. tonight and something tells me you'd find a way to put me on the cover of the next issue.
{DIALOGUE}: Am I right?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks at their faces.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They cannot disagree.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm learning the game.
{META_DATA}: (beat, shrug)
{DIALOGUE}: We fucked up.
{DIALOGUE}: We made friends with him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BEN
{DIALOGUE}: Next time we'll all be more professional.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe so.
{META_DATA}: (beat, an odd thought)
{DIALOGUE}: But God forbid, the day comes when selling yourself is as important as the music you make.
{META_DATA}: (rueful, to Hendrix on the wall)
{DIALOGUE}: You might have died at the right time, my friend.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JANN
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you for visiting.
{DIALOGUE}: Good luck.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL
{DIALOGUE}: Do what you want, but the story is true.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LONG SHOT RUSSELL
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: at the entrance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Raises his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RUSSELL (cont'd)
{DIALOGUE}: Good evening!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 162A EXT. SAN FRANCISCO - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Russell stands outside, a traveling man with no where to go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Oddly, and in a way that surprises him, the world begins to speak to him again... little noises everywhere, turning into a music of its own.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a beautiful and compelling "silence."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He thrusts his hands deep in his pockets, and takes a breath of life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His head filling again with the music of the world, he begins to walk down the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Very naturally, and quite randomly, he is noticed by young passersby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They can't help it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks like a star.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They can't quite figure out who it is, but it's someone, and they begin to follow him down the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Unbeknownst to him as he walks along, deep in thought, a small crowd begins to form... following him.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 163 INT. BREAKFAST TABLE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A quiet kitchen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anita has been cooking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A substantial breakfast has been placed on the table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sausage, orange juice... and now Anita sets down a plate of pancakes, with syrup and butter, in front of her mother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: William watches his mother facing an old enemy - white sugar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANITA
{DIALOGUE}: They're called pancakes.
{DIALOGUE}: Who knows when we'll be together again.
{DIALOGUE}: Splurge.
{DIALOGUE}: It's what most people call breakfast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mom looks at her children, and takes a breath.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELAINE
{DIALOGUE}: I went through your records.
{DIALOGUE}: And I found a song to play for you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She goes to the stereo and puts on a record.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two children eye each other - what's coming next?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: (Song to be chosen) The two kids eye each other again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Self-consciously avoiding their gaze, Mom sits and toys with her breakfast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a song she clearly wants them to hear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's a song from the heart.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They look at her, amazed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Elaine looks up, regards her family.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Somehow they're back at this table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They continue eating breakfast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 164 ON SIDEWALK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bam.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A bundle of bound Rolling Stone Magazines lands on the newsstand pavement with a thud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Someone reaches in to cut the cord, as the magazines puff up into view.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the new issue, with Russell Hammond on the cover.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The title: Stillwater Runs Deep.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just another stack of magazines waiting to be places in the racks.
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music segues to Led Zeppelin's "Four Sticks."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Penny Lane's sleeping Polaroid shots of our characters, featuring a few self-portraits.
{META_DATA}: THE END
